= \n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Perak}}\n| established_title1              = Establishment\n| established_date1               = Around 1880\n| established_title2              = Granted States Capital status\n| established_date2               = 31 May 1937\n| established_title3              = Granted Municipality status\n| established_date3               = 31 May 1962\n| established_title4              = Granted City status\n| established_date4               = 27 May 1988\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Rumaizi Baharin\n| area_total_km2                  = 643\n| area_total_sq_mi                = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| elevation_m                     = 21.95\n| elevation_ft                    = 72\n| population_total                = 657,892\n| population_as_of                = 2010\n| population_density_km2          = 1023\n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| population_metro                = 737,861<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521201742/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Malaysia|Postcode]]\n| postal_code                     = 30xxx, 31xxx\n| area_code                       = 05\n| area_code_type                  = \n| iso_code                        = \n| website                         = {{URL|mbi.gov.my}}\n| unemployment_rate               = \n| translit_lang1_type1            = [[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]\n| translit_lang1_info1            = \u0625\u06a4\u0648\u0647\n| translit_lang1_type2            = [[Chinese language|Chinese]]\n| translit_lang1_info2            = \u6021\u4fdd\n| translit_lang1_type3            = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| translit_lang1_info3            = \u0b88\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcb\n| timezone                        = [[Malaysian Standard Time|MST]]\n| utc_offset                      = +8\n| timezone_DST                    = Not observed\n}}\n\n'''Ipoh''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|i\u02d0|p|o\u028a}}) is the capital city of the [[Malaysia]]n [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|state]] of [[Perak]]. Located by the [[Kinta River]], it is nearly {{Convert|180|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Kuala Lumpur]] and {{Convert|123|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in neighbouring [[Penang]]. {{As of|2010}}, Ipoh contained a population of 657,892, making it the [[List of cities in Malaysia by population|third largest city in Malaysia by population]].<ref name=\"st1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010 (page 1 & 8)|publisher=Department of Statistics, Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205090002/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|archivedate=5 February 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOriginally a village, Ipoh began to grow rapidly in the 1880s after huge deposits of [[tin]] were discovered within its vicinity.<ref name=\":0\" /> By 1895, it was the second largest town within the [[Federated Malay States]], which also consisted of [[Selangor]], [[Negeri Sembilan]] and [[Pahang]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbi.gov.my/ms/pelawat/info-ipoh/page/0/1|title=Info Ipoh: Halaman 2 dari 2 {{!}} Portal Rasmi Majlis Bandaraya Ipoh (MBI)|website=mbi.gov.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> Ipoh was declared a city in 1988.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> However, following the depletion of its tin deposits and the collapse of tin prices in the 1970s, the city suffered decades of decline and neglect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/travel/malaysia/2012/01/09/ipoh/|title=Ipoh - Malaysia {{!}} The Star Online|last=Tam|first=Susan|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/02/22/the-city-that-tin-built/|title=The city that tin built|last=Tan|first=Peter|date=2015-02-21|website=BorneoPost Online {{!}} Borneo, Malaysia, Sarawak Daily News|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sleepy-ipoh-awakens|title=Sleepy Ipoh awakens|last=hermes|date=2016-03-22|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2017-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theedgeproperty.com.my/content/old-town-restored-rightful-place-history-ipoh|title=Old Town restored to rightful place in history of Ipoh|website=theedgeproperty.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, Ipoh's popularity as a tourist destination has been significantly boosted by efforts to conserve its [[British Empire|British]] colonial-era architecture.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The city is also well known for its [[Ipoh cuisine|cuisine]] and natural attractions, such as its limestone hills and caves within which Buddhist temples were built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipohecho.com.my/v4/article/2015/05/16/caves-of-the-kinta-valley|title=Ipoh Echo {{!}} Caves of the Kinta Valley|last=net|first=powered by iosc dot|website=IpohEcho.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> In addition, Ipoh has managed to maintain its reputation as one of the cleanest cities in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/08/14/ipoh-is-malaysias-cleanest-city/|title=Ipoh is Malaysia's cleanest city - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=thestar.com.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIpoh's location between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] has made it a major land transportation hub within [[Peninsular Malaysia|West Malaysia]], with both the [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu|Malayan Railway]]'s [[KTM West Coast Railway Line|West Coast Line]] and the [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North-South Expressway]] cutting through the city. Aside from the land transportation links, Ipoh is also served by the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]].\n\nIpoh is known as the Hipster Capital of Malaysia by various tourism rating and official agencies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1160937/ipohs-hipster-town-image-reason-for-new-found-fame-mb-says|title=Malay Mail - Ipoh Hipster Town Image|last=|first=|date=|work=The Malay Mail|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://says.com/my/news/ipoh-listed-in-lonely-planet-best-in-asia-2016|title=SAYS|last=|first=|date=|work=SAYS DOT COM|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/03/03/from-sleepy-city-to-international-draw-new-york-times-hails-ipoh-as-hip-and-mustvisit-holiday-destin/|title=The Star Malaysia|last=|first=|date=|work=The Star Malaysia|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timetravelturtle.com/hipster-ipoh-malaysia/|title=Time Travel Turtle|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Travel Turtle|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIpoh grew out from the Malay village of Paloh along the banks of the Kinta River in the 1880s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://db.ipohworld.org/photo/pdf/3875_wzhem140612.pdf|title=The History of Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Its geographic location in the rich tin-bearing valley of the [[Kinta River]] made it a natural centre of growth.\n\nThe Great Fire of Ipoh in 1892 destroyed over half the town, but also presented an opportunity to rebuild the town in a more orderly grid pattern. Ipoh was subsequently rebuilt in time for the second tin rush and grew rapidly as a result of the booming tin mining industry, particularly in the 1920s and 1930s.\n\nA local [[Hakka people|Hakka]] miner, millionaire Yau Tet Shin, started developing a large tract of the town in the early 1930s, today known as the 'New Town', from the eastern bank of the [[Kinta River]] to Greentown.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\">[http://www.ipohworld.org/blog/?p=762 Ipohworld\u2019s World \u00bb Yau Tet Shin\u2019s New Town Under Construction 1908]. Ipohworld.org. Retrieved 27 September 2013.</ref> In 1937, Ipoh was made the capital of Perak, replacing [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]].\n\nIpoh was invaded by the Japanese on 15 December 1941. In March 1942, the Japanese Civil Administration or Perak Shu Seicho was set up at the [[St. Michael's Institution]]. After the liberation of Malaya by British forces, Ipoh remained the capital of Perak to this day.<ref>Khoo Salma Nasution & Abdur-Razzaq Lubis, ''Kinta Valley: Pioneering Malaysia's Modern Development'', Ipoh: Perak Academy, 2005. pp. 273\u2013292</ref>\n\nThe decline of the tin mining industry during the latter half of the 20th century caused the growth of Ipoh to stagnate.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} With the closure of the tin mines, its urban population was forced to seek employment in other cities within Malaysia. In spite of this, Ipoh remains one of the largest cities in Malaysia in terms of population, with tourism now a main driver of the city's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.world-guides.com/asia/malaysia/perak/ipoh/ipoh_history.html|title=Ipoh History Facts and Timeline: Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia|website=world-guides.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIpoh gained Municipal status in 1962, and in 1988, was declared a city by the then [[Sultan of Perak]], [[Azlan Shah of Perak|Sultan Azlan Shah]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Geography ==\n{{Location map many|Malaysia Perak Ipoh|width=300|float=left\n|caption=Locations of Ipoh and its suburbs\n|lat1=4.597222|long1=101.075|label1_size=75 |label1='''Ipoh'''|position1=left\n|lat2=4.720754|long2=101.1212|label2_size=65 |label2=[[Chemor]]|position2=left|mark2=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat3=4.61831|long3=101.140884|label3_size=65 |label3=[[Tambun]]|position3=right|mark=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat4=4.638596|long4=101.0636|label4_size=65 |label4=[[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]]|position4=left|mark4=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat5=4.529513|long5=101.129836|label5_size=65 |label5=[[Simpang Pulai]]|position5=right|mark5=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat6=4.56836|long6=101.050314|label6_size=65 |label6=[[Menglembu]]|position6=left|mark6=Cyan pog.svg\n}}\n\n=== Topography ===\nIpoh is in the state of [[Perak]], which is in the northern part of [[Peninsular Malaysia]]. The city is in the middle of the [[Kinta Valley]], on the bank of the [[Kinta River]] and the confluence of smaller rivers, Sungai Pinji and Sungai Pari. The city is surrounded by limestone hills, which can be found around suburban areas to the northeast, east and southeast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiahotelreview.com/perak/destination/limestone-hill.shtml |title=Limestone Hills (Bukit Batu Kapur), Ipoh, PERAK \u2013 Malaysia Travel Review |publisher=Malaysiahotelreview.com |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Kledang mountain range stretches from the north to the west of the city. This range runs parallel to the [[Bintang Mountains|Bintang mountain range]] with the [[Perak River]] flowing on its left bank and the [[Kinta River]] to its right. This range is interrupted to the north of Ipoh by a tributary of the [[Perak River]] called the Pelus River, which is sourced from the [[Titiwangsa Mountains|Titiwangsa mountain range]], which runs to the east of Ipoh.<ref>{{cite book |last= Jacq-Hergoualc'h |first= Michel |author2=Victoria Hobson |title= The Malay Peninsula: Crossroads of the Maritime Silk Road (100 BC \u2013 1300 AD) |publisher= [[Brill Publishers|BRILL]] |date=September 2002 |isbn= 90-04-11973-6}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\nIpoh features a [[tropical rainforest climate]] more subject to the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] than the [[trade wind]]s and with very rare [[cyclone]]s so an equatorial climate. Temperatures are about the same throughout the year, showing little variation. The city's average temperature is {{Convert|28|C}}. Ipoh sees high precipitation throughout the year with an average of {{Convert|200|mm|abbr=on}} of rain each month and averaging {{Convert|2427.9|mm|abbr=on}} of rain per year. The wettest month is October where on average {{Convert|297.2|mm|abbr=on}} of rain is seen. Ipoh's driest month is January which has {{Convert|132.3|mm|abbr=on}} of rain fall on average.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Ipoh\n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| Jan high C = 32.9\n| Feb high C = 33.7\n| Mar high C = 33.9\n| Apr high C = 33.7\n| May high C = 33.5\n| Jun high C = 33.3\n| Jul high C = 33.0\n| Aug high C = 33.0\n| Sep high C = 32.5\n| Oct high C = 32.4\n| Nov high C = 32.1\n| Dec high C = 32.1\n| year high C = 33.0\n| Jan low C = 22.6\n| Feb low C = 23.0\n| Mar low C = 23.4\n| Apr low C = 23.9\n| May low C = 24.0\n| Jun low C = 23.7\n| Jul low C = 23.2\n| Aug low C = 23.3\n| Sep low C = 23.2\n| Oct low C = 23.1\n| Nov low C = 23.1\n| Dec low C = 22.8\n| year low C = 23.3\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 132.3\n| Feb rain mm = 149.8\n| Mar rain mm = 169.9\n| Apr rain mm = 259.1\n| May rain mm = 210.9\n| Jun rain mm = 151.8\n| Jul rain mm = 156.6\n| Aug rain mm = 157.8\n| Sep rain mm = 216.0\n| Oct rain mm = 297.2\n| Nov rain mm = 275.4\n| Dec rain mm = 251.1\n| year rain mm = 2427.9\n| unit rain days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan rain days = 9\n| Feb rain days = 10\n| Mar rain days = 12\n| Apr rain days = 14\n| May rain days = 14\n| Jun rain days = 10\n| Jul rain days = 10\n| Aug rain days = 12\n| Sep rain days = 15\n| Oct rain days = 18\n| Nov rain days = 18\n| Dec rain days = 15\n| year rain days = 157\n| source 1 = [[World Meteorological Organisation]]<ref name= WMO>{{cite web\n| url = http://worldweather.wmo.int/020/c00077.htm\n| title = World Weather Information Service&nbsp;\u2013 Ipoh\n| publisher = World Meteorological Organisation\n| accessdate = 7 May 2014}}</ref>\n| date     = May 2014}}\n\n=== Limestone caves ===\n[[File:Gua Tempurung.jpg|thumb|The Gua Tempurung Limestone Caves|left]]\n\n[[File:SAM POH TONG LOKE 399.jpg|thumb|[[Sam Poh Tong]], one of the many temples in Ipoh]][[File:Gunung Lang.jpg|thumb|Lang Mountains in Ipoh|left]]\n\nLimestone outcrops rise on the outskirts of Ipoh. There are many caves in these outcrops; cave temples are built in some.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060706051626/http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 July 2006 |title=Home |publisher=Cavesofmalaysia.com |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref> [[Sam Poh Tong]] is a notable one along with Kek Lok Tong (Chinese: \u6975\u6a02\u6d1e; Cavern of Utmost Happiness), which lies on the other side of the same outcrop. It is accessible through the Gunung Rapat housing area. It has a clean, quiet and cool environment. Other cave temples in Ipoh include Ling Sen Tong, Nan Tian Tong, Kwan Yin Tong and Perak Tong.\n\n[[Gua Tempurung]], near Gopeng south of Ipoh, is a show cave open to the public and popular among [[Caving|spelunkers]]. More than {{Convert|3|km|abbr=on}} long, it is one of the longest caves in Peninsular Malaysia. Part of it has been developed with electric lighting and walkways, and there are tours of different lengths and difficulty. A river passage runs about {{Convert|1.6|km|abbr=on}} through the hill. There are five very large chambers and some stalactites and stalagmites.\n\n== Famous for  \" Malay, Chinese, Indian\" Cuisine  ==\n{{Main|Ipoh cuisine}}\nIpoh has a vibrant food scene with a vast proliferation of hawker centres and restaurants. It is well known for dishes such as \"Sar Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u6c99\u6cb3\u7c89}}) a complete one-dish rice noodle meal with prawn, meat, fish, vegetables and a savoury sauce. Other well known dishes from Ipoh include \"Hor Hee\", flat white rice noodles served with fish cakes and/or fish balls, \"Nga Choi Kai\" ({{zh|c=\u82bd\u83dc\u9e21}}), chicken with soy sauce and beansprouts topped with pepper,\"Kai Shi Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u9e21\u4e1d\u6cb3\u7c89}}) rice noodles with Chicken, \"[[Hakka Mee]]\" ({{zh|c=\u5ba2\u5bb6\u9eb5}}), yellow rice noodles served with mince meat (pork) sauce, \"Tau Fu Fa\", soybean pudding, and Ipoh's famous pastry \"[[Heong Peng]]\" ({{zh|c=\u9999\u9905}}), literally translated to \"fragrant biscuit\". The city is well known in Malaysia for its \"[[Ipoh white coffee]]\" where the coffee beans are roasted with palm-oil margarine and the resulting coffee is served with condensed milk. Ipoh is also known for its fresh fruits such as Pomelo, Durian and Seedless Guava. Ipoh also the home of the famous Ipoh Nasi Kandar or Nasi Vanggey. The dish which is very famous among local citizen and most favorite afternoon dish. When it come's to malay cuisine the best part is their place set up like a village home serving amazing home food example: Nasi lemak with fried Country chicken spicy sambal \"Restoran nasi lemak ayam kampung\" use waze to travel this place. Did you know that IPOH ORIGINAL KACANG PUTIH which means IPOH INDIAN SNACKS is now world famous snack and Indians here now exporting their signature snacks to world wide. Little India is big street which is located in ipoh, famous for Indian cuisine like vegetarian : krishna bhagawan, anandha bhagawan  and for non vegetarian : Thirupathy vilas , old town chapthi . Furthermore, to taste the Authentic South Indian & Clay pot rice visit RESTORAN SRI NAVA JOHTHI 1996 which is located in BUNTONG,ipoh. Their dish normally less preventatives and more to a village method and Clay pot rice is their signature menu which mix with real herbs & spices can blow your mind.    \n\nIn recent years Ipoh has seen an increase in international restaurants, bars and gastropubs have become popular with locals and tourists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ipoh's bars, gastropubs and nightlife |url=http://travel-tourist-information-guide.com/malaysia-ipoh-bars-clubs-night-life-going-out-drinking-entertainment|website=Travel-Tourist-Information-Guide.com|accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Economy  ==\nThe early history Ipoh as a settlement was due to its mining industry although it was playing second fiddle to Gopeng, some 19&nbsp;km / 12 miles to the south.\nIpoh was once, one of the richest cities in Malaysia as well as South East Asia back in the days when tin was king. During the 1980s when tin prices collapsed, the economy of Ipoh was hit particularly hard. However, recently the city gain some momentum. By 2017, the city will open the first Movie Animation Theme Park (MAPS), which is the first ever in South East Asia. Tourism is booming in the city, and many shops in old town Ipoh is being transform into chic caf\u00e9. \nThe city of Ipoh also host some big multi national corporations. Kuala Lumpur Kepong (KLK) Berhad, a palm oil company, which is also among the top 15 biggest companies in Malaysia (By revenue) has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nBatu Kawan Berhad (Which is the biggest shareholder of KLK), an investment company also has its headquarters in Malaysia. \nHovid Berhad, a pharmaceutical company, which is also the first Malaysian companies to introduce generic drugs overseas also has its headquarters in Ipoh. Ipoh also is well known for its white coffee. Old Town Berhad, which is a food & beverage public listed company, specializing in white coffee has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nThere are a few other public listed companies in Ipoh such as Perak Transit Berhad, Tasek Cement Berhad, DKLS Industries Berhad, Wellcall Holding Berhad, Rubberex Berhad, Perak Corp, etc. Ipoh also host some foreign multi national companies Malaysian headquarters. Some of the foreign MNC's in Ipoh is, Finisar, Voith, ITL Asia pacific, Sagami Manufacturers, etc.\n\n== Cityscape ==\n[[File:Ipoh_58.jpg|thumb|Ipoh Skyline]]\n[[File:Ipoh, Perak.jpg|thumb|Jalan Laxamana]]\n\n=== The Old Town ===\nThe Old Town is west of the Kinta River. There is a vibrant commercial district with many historical 'shop-houses' centred around Leech Street ({{zh|c=\u70c8\u6cbb\u8857}}; now Jalan Bandar Timah). Other notable features include:\n* [[Ipoh railway station]] in neo-classical/[[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] style nicknamed the \"Taj Mahal of Ipoh\".\n* Ipoh Town Hall, an [[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] municipal building located across the road from the Railway Station.\n* Padang Ipoh or Ipoh Field is on Jalan S.P. Seenivasagam. The field is surrounded by historic buildings that feature classic colonial architecture, including the mock-Tudor style Ipoh Club, FMS Bar, HSBC Building and the [[St Michael's Institution]] secondary school.\n* The [[Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh]], officially named SMK Methodist (ACS), is located along Lahat Road.\n* [[Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Anderson]] is the most well-known secondary school with more than 100 years of history, located beside the General Hospital of Ipoh. This school has been producing numerous of figures in the country.\n* [[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh, is a public secondary school in Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia. It is situated on Jalan S. P. Seenivasagam, formerly Clayton Road.\n* [[Han Chin Pet Soo (History Museum)|Han Chin Pet Soo]], the Hakka Tin Miner's Club, located on Jalan Bijeh Timah (formerly Treacher Street) has been restored and turned into Malaysia's First Hakka Tin Mining Museum.\n* Muzium Darul Ridzuan is a historical museum of Perak, in a pretty former tin-mining tycoon's mansion on Jalan Kuala Kangsar.\n*Concubine Lane or better known locally as Yi Lai Hong in Cantonese is a narrow and small lane located off Jalan Bandar Timah (Leech Street) in Old Town, Ipoh. It now has different restaurants, souvenir and gift shops and an entirely respectable hotel. To some locals, Concubine Lane is already becoming too busy.\n*Ipoh wall art murals drawn by talented street art artists clearly breathes in new life into Ipoh Old Town city. The murals do relive a sense of nostalgic moments related to Ipoh\u2019s heritage and culture. It is now a tourist attraction.\n[[File:Old Uncle with White Coffee.jpg|thumb|One of the 7 wall art murals drawn by Ernest Zacharevic in Ipoh old town.]]\n*[[Birch Memorial Clock Tower]] is a historical landmark which is located near the Ipoh State Mosque or commonly known as [[Sultan Idris Shah II Mosque]]. The clock tower was built to commemorate [[James W. W. Birch]], the first British Resident in Perak who was killed on 2 November 1875 at Pasir Salak.\n\n=== The New Town ===\n[[File:Tmn d.r.jpg|thumb|D.R. Seenivasagam Park, formerly Coronation Park]]\nThe so-called New Town, to the east of the Kinta River, was developed by [[Yau Tet Shin]] around 1908.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\" /> The New Town houses the [[Perak Medical University]] and [[Ipoh City Hall]] building, among others. There are numerous shops, shopping malls, and hotels.\n\nD. R. Seenivasagam Park (Coronation Park), located in the heart of Ipoh (New Town), is known for its scenery and recreational facilities.{{fact|date=March 2019}} It comprises recreational fields, an artificial lake filled with fish, a nursery for potted plants and a children's traffic playground.  The latest addition is the newly landscaped [[Japanese garden]] featuring a Japanese [[Koi|carp]] pond.\n\n== Sports ==\n\nFor golf, the courses are the Royal Perak Golf Club off Jalan Sultan Azlan Shah (Tiger Lane), the Meru Golf Club in [[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]], and Clearwater Sanctuary Golf Club en route to [[Batu Gajah]].\n\nOther sports venues include the Kilat Club in Pasir Pinji, Ipoh Field (Padang Ipoh) in the Old Town, the [[Polo]] Grounds, and the Iskandar Polo Club, in Ampang Baru.\n\nThe [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] is an annual international men's [[field hockey]] tournament held in Ipoh.\n\nIpoh has a fully equipped sports complex known as Kompleks Sukan MBI or ''MBI Sports Complex''.\n\nAmong the facilities located within the Complex is the Stadium Perak or [[Perak Stadium]]. [[Perak Stadium]] is the home of [[Perak FA|Perak The Bos Gaurus]] who playing in [[Malaysia Super League]].\n\n== Governance ==\n[[File:Ipoh City Council.jpg|thumb|[[Ipoh City Council]]]]\n\nThe [[Ipoh City Council]] governs the city. Datuk Zamri Man, appointed in August 2015, is the current mayor of Ipoh.<ref>{{Cite web|title = New mayor for Ipoh sworn in \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|url = http://www.thestar.com.my/Metro/Community/2015/08/10/New-mayor-for-Ipoh-sworn-in/|website = The Star|location=Malaysia|accessdate = 11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIpoh is divided into two parliamentary constituencies: ''Ipoh Barat'' (Ipoh West) and ''Ipoh Timur'' (Ipoh East). The parliamentary seat for ''Ipoh Timur'' is held by DAP Representative, Su Keong Siong, which was formerly held by [[Lim Kit Siang]] while the seat for ''Ipoh Barat'' is held by fellow DAP leader, [[M. Kulasegaran]].<ref>[http://temanpetunjuk.blogspot.com/2009/02/analisa-dewan-undangan-negeri-dun-perak.html]{{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nIpoh remains one of [[Malaysia]]'s largest cities. It is the third largest city in Malaysia. As of 2010, the municipal area of Ipoh has a population of 657,892.<ref name=\"census 2010\">{{cite web|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf|publisher=Department of Statistics Malaysia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227011347/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref> It ranks as the seventh most [[List of urban areas in Malaysia by population|populous urban centre]] in Malaysia (2010).<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n\nThe following is based on Department of Statistics Malaysia 2010 census.<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=3| Ethnic groups in Ipoh, 2010\n|-\n! [[Ethnicity]] !! Population !! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] || 290,165 || 44.11%\n|-\n| [[Bumiputera_(Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] || 253,592 || 38.55%\n|-\n| [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] ||  92,587 || 14.07%\n|-\n| Others || 1,559 || 0.2%\n|-\n| Non-Malaysian || 19,989 || 3.04%\n|}\n\n=== Toponymy ===\nThe name Ipoh is derived from a local tree, ''Pohon Epu'' or now more commonly known as [[Upas Tree|''Pokok Ipoh'']]. The sap of this plant is poisonous and was used by [[Orang Asli]] ([[indigenous peoples]] in [[Malay language|Malay]]) to coat the tips of the darts of their blowpipes for hunting.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Sultan Azlan Shah Airport.JPG|thumb|[[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]]]]\n* Trunk roads: The old interstate [[Malaysia Federal Route 1|Route]] {{JKR|1}} connects Ipoh with other major towns and cities in peninsular Malaysia, for example to [[Alor Setar]], [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]] and [[Penang]] to the north and [[Tapah]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Seremban]] and even [[Johor Bahru]] in the south. Motorists from the east coast can use [[Malaysia Federal Route 4|highway]] {{JKR|4}} (from [[Gerik]]) in northern Perak or {{JKR|185}} (from [[Cameron Highlands]]).\n* Highway: The new [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North\u2013South Expressway]] {{MES-E|1}} is a faster and more efficient alternative to Route 1. However, certain towns like [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]] can only be accessible via Route 1.\n* Train: [[Ipoh railway station|Ipoh's railway station]] is operated by [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu]] (KTM) and is in the Old Town (however, it does not have intra-city travel like in [[Kuala Lumpur]]). The railway only connects Ipoh with neighbouring towns and cities. The station is a stately building, referred to by locals as the 'Taj Mahal' of Ipoh. [[KTM Intercity]] began the Shuttle Train Service between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and Ipoh from 1 December 2008 while the modern [[Electric Train System]] (ETS) shuttle began from 12 August 2010 with average {{Convert|145|km/h|abbr=on}} speed, plying Ipoh-Seremban route, cut the travelling distance between Ipoh and [[Kuala Lumpur]] into 120&nbsp;minutes. There are 10 dedicated shuttle train services between these two cities daily which begins at 5&nbsp;am from both the stations. Travel time between the cities was expected to be reduced from three hours to two hours and fifteen minutes when the new set of EMU trains arrived in mid-2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119155613/http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |title=Malaysia / Perak / The Ipoh Railway Station |publisher=Cockatoo.com |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref>\n* Bus: The inter-city bus terminal is located at [[Amanjaya Integrated Bus Terminal]] in [[Bandar Meru Raya]], just north of the city.\n* Air:  the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]] is the only airport in Ipoh. It is near [[Gunung Rapat]]. Domestic flights and international ones are available. [[Scoot]] and [[AirAsia]] provides daily flights out of Ipoh to [[Singapore]] [[Changi Airport]] while [[Batik Air Malaysia]] provides daily flights to [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]].\nThere are also planned flights to Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand and China with talks of a new airport soon.\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|List of schools in Perak}}\n\nThis is a list of schools in Ipoh, Perak.\n*Sekolah Izzuddin Shah \n*[[Sekolah Tuanku Abdul Rahman]] \n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Tanjung Rambutan\n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Seri Puteri\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan(T)ST.Philomena Convent, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Dato Panglima'Kinta, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*SMJK Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*Tarcisian Convent School, Ipoh (TCS)\n*Anderson School, Ipoh\n*Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh\n*[[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Tasek, Ipoh \n*Methodist Girls Secondary School (MGS), Ipoh\n*Perak Girls Secondary School (PGS), Ipoh\n*[[SMK Main Convent]], Ipoh\n*Wesley Methodist School, Ipoh\n*Ipoh International School (Private)\n*Fairview International School, Ipoh\n*Perak Yuk Choy High School (Private) \n*Poi Lam High School (Private) \u6021\u4fdd\u57f9\u5357\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u5b66 \n*Shen Jai High School, Ipoh \u6021\u4fdd\u6df1\u658b\u4e2d\u5b66\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Kerajaan, Sungai Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Perak Sangeetha Sabha, Ipoh\n*SMK Rapat Setia, Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Pasir Puteh, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*SMK Seri Keledang, Ipoh\n*SMK Menglembu, Ipoh\n*SMJK Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Sam Tet, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*[[SMJK Sam Tet]], Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*SMK Dato Ahmad Said\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*SMJK Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (1)\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (2)\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (ACS), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (P) Methodist, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Haji Mahmud Chemor, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Kuala Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jalan Pegoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jelapang\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Marian Convent,Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Raja Ekram, Ipoh\n*SMK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) Royal Princess School \"Cluster School\"\n*SRK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) \n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Seri Ampang, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (1), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (2), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Chung Shan\n\n== Theme Parks ==\nThere are several theme parks in Ipoh, including the Sunway Lost World of Tambun <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sunwaylostworldoftambun.com/|title=Lost World of Tambun Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and Movies Animated Park Studios (MAPS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsperak.com/|title=Movies Animation Park, Ipoh Official Website|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207000455/http://www.mapsperak.com/|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\nFilm and Television:\n* [[Angie Cheong]]\n* [[Mimi Chu]]\n* [[Iqram Dinzly]]\n* [[Mamat Khalid]]\n* [[Peter Pek]]\n* [[Afdlin Shauki]]\n* [[Patrick Teoh]]\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]]\nMusic:\n* [[Guang Liang|Michael Wong]]\n* [[Jamal Abdillah]]\n* [[Shila Amzah]]\n* [[Ning Baizura]]\n* [[Francissca Peter]]\n* [[:ms:Sophia Liana|Sophia Liana]]\n* Sam Chin Neng of [[Fuying & Sam]]\nSports: (Badminton):\n* [[Koo Kien Keat]]\n* [[Choong Tan Fook]]\n* [[Lee Wan Wah]]\n* [[Cheah Soon Kit]]\n* [[Wong Pei Tty]]\n* [[Wong Mew Choo]]\nSports ([[Association football|Football]]):\n* [[Nazirul Naim]]\n* [[Chan Kok Heng]]\n* [[Muhamad Khalid Jamlus]]\nSports (Others):\n* [[Tony Underwood]] (Rugby)\n* [[Nur Suryani Mohd Taibi]] (Sports shooting)\n* [[Leong Mun Yee]] (Diving)\nBusiness:\n* [[David Ho Sue San]] of [[Hovid Berhad]] & Carotech Berhad,\n* [[Lee Loy Seng]] (founder of Kuala Lumpur Kepong Berhad),\n* Dr. [[Wong Jeh Shyan]] CEO of CommerceNet Singapore Limited,\n* [[Koon Yew Yin]] Founder of [[IJM Corporation Bhd]] and [[Gamuda Berhad]]\nPolitics:\n* [[Yeoh Ghim Seng]]\n* [[Yeoh Eng-kiong|Dr Yeoh Eng Kiong]]\n* [[S. J. V. Chelvanayakam]]\n* [[Ahmad Husni Hanadzlah]]\n* [[D. R. Seenivasagam]]\n* [[Lim Keng Yaik]]\n* [[Lee Lam Thye]]\n* [[Chang Lih Kang]]\n* [[Lee Chuan How]]\nHistorical:\n* [[Yusof bin Ishak]] (president of Singapore)\n* [[Leong Sin Nam]]\n* [[Wu Lien-teh]]\n* [[Foo Choo Choon]