opulation_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[China Standard Time|China Standard]]\n|utc_offset             = +8\n|coordinates            = {{coord|23|45|N|114|42|E|region:CN-44|display=it}}\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = <!--  [[Postal code of China|Postal code]] -->\n|postal_code            = 517000\n|area_code              = 0762\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-GD-16]]\n|blank_name             =<!-- [[GDP]] -->\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =<!-- GDP per capita -->\n|blank1_info            =\n|blank2_name            =[[Licence plates of the People's Republic of China|License Plate]]\n|blank2_info            ={{lang|zh-cn|\u7ca4P}}\n|website                =\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|pic=HY name.png\n|piccap=\"Heyuan\", as written in Chinese calligraphy\n|picsize=130px\n|c=\u6cb3\u6e90\n|p=H\u00e9yu\u00e1n\n|mi={{IPAc-cmn|h|e|2|.|yuan|2}}\n|gr=Heryuan\n|w=Ho<sup>2</sup>-y\u00fcan<sup>2</sup>\n|psp=Hoyun\n|j=Ho4jyun4\n|ci={{IPAc-yue|h|o|4|.|j|yun|4}}\n|y=H\u00f2hy\u00f9hn\n|l=River spring\n|showflag=py\n|order=st\n}}\n'''H\u00e9yu\u00e1n''' ({{zh|c=\u6cb3\u6e90}}) is a [[prefecture-level city]] of [[Guangdong]] province in the [[People's Republic of China]]. At the 2010 census, its population was 2,950,195 whom 903,871 lived in the built-up (''or metro'') area made of Yuancheng urban District and Dongyuan County largely being urbanized. Zijin County itself is quickly being conurbated in the agglomeration. The majority of the people are [[Hakka people|Hakka]].\nThe city includes many rainforests and the largest lake in Guangdong: [[Xinfengjiang Reservoir]]. The literal meaning of the city's name is \"origin of the river\". It has recently been officially titled as the \"Hometown of the Dinosaur in China\", due to the thousands of dinosaur egg fossils that have been unearthed in its vicinity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Qian|first1=Wang|title=Heyuan, Hometown of the Dinosaur|url=http://www.china.org.cn/english/2005/Apr/125456.htm|accessdate=5 August 2015|agency=China.org.cn|date=11 April 2005}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nHeyuan is located in the north-east region of Guangdong, upper reach of [[Dong River (China)|Dong River]] at its confluence with the [[Xingeng River]]. Its latitude spans 23\u00b0 10'\u201324\u00b0 50' N, and longitude 114\u00b0 13'\u2013115\u00b0 35' E. It borders [[Huizhou]] to the south, [[Ganzhou]] ([[Jiangxi]]) to the north, [[Meizhou]] to the east and [[Shaoguan]] to the west. Heyuan is a regional hub that connects the coastal areas of Guangdong and the interior countryside.\n\nHeyuan is rich in natural resources and fertile land. There are {{convert|1000|km2|abbr=on}} of cultivated land, {{convert|13600|km\u00b2|abbr=on}} of hilly land, and {{convert|640|km\u00b2}} of water area. Many mineral deposits such as iron ore, tungsten, tin, fluorite are found in Heyuan.\n\n=== Climate ===\nHeyuan has a monsoon-influenced [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cfa''), with short, mild to warm winters, and long, hot, humid summers. Winter begins sunny and dry but becomes progressively wetter and cloudier. Spring is generally overcast and often rainy, while summer continues to be rainy though is much sunnier; there are 9.1 days annually with {{convert|50|mm|2|abbr=on}} of rainfall. Autumn is sunny and dry. The monthly 24-hour average temperature ranges from {{convert|13.1|\u00b0C|1}} in January to {{convert|28.5|\u00b0C|1}} in July, and the annual mean is {{convert|21.83|\u00b0C|1}}. The annual rainfall is  {{convert|1927|mm|0|abbr=on}}, and is delivered in bulk (47%) from April to June. With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 23% in March to 55% in October and November, the city receives 1,842 hours of bright sunshine annually.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|metric first=y\n|single line=y \n|collapsed = Y\n|location = Heyuan (1981\u22122010)\n|Jan high C = 18.4\n|Feb high C = 18.9\n|Mar high C = 21.7\n|Apr high C = 26.0\n|May high C = 29.7\n|Jun high C = 31.6\n|Jul high C = 33.4\n|Aug high C = 33.3\n|Sep high C = 31.8\n|Oct high C = 29.2\n|Nov high C = 25.0\n|Dec high C = 20.3\n|Jan mean C = 13.1\n|Feb mean C = 14.3\n|Mar mean C = 17.4\n|Apr mean C = 22.0\n|May mean C = 25.5\n|Jun mean C = 27.4\n|Jul mean C = 28.5\n|Aug mean C = 28.4\n|Sep mean C = 27.1\n|Oct mean C = 24.1\n|Nov mean C = 19.5\n|Dec mean C = 14.7\n|year mean C = \n|Jan low C = 9.6\n|Feb low C = 11.2\n|Mar low C = 14.3\n|Apr low C = 19.1\n|May low C = 22.4\n|Jun low C = 24.5\n|Jul low C = 25.2\n|Aug low C = 25.2\n|Sep low C = 23.7\n|Oct low C = 20.2\n|Nov low C = 15.6\n|Dec low C = 10.8\n|Jan record high C = 28.3 |Jan record low C = 0.9\n|Feb record high C = 29.9 |Feb record low C = 1.8\n|Mar record high C = 33.0 |Mar record low C = 2.0\n|Apr record high C = 33.8 |Apr record low C = 7.9\n|May record high C = 36.0 |May record low C = 15.0\n|Jun record high C = 38.6 |Jun record low C = 18.6\n|Jul record high C = 39.0 |Jul record low C = 18.5\n|Aug record high C = 38.8 |Aug record low C = 21.4\n|Sep record high C = 37.5 |Sep record low C = 16.0\n|Oct record high C = 36.6 |Oct record low C = 10.3\n|Nov record high C = 34.2 |Nov record low C = 3.8\n|Dec record high C = 29.9 |Dec record low C = -0.7\n|year high C=  |year low C= \n|year high F = |year low F =\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 51.2\n|Feb precipitation mm = 96.0\n|Mar precipitation mm = 160.3\n|Apr precipitation mm = 230.8\n|May precipitation mm = 290.0\n|Jun precipitation mm = 351.3\n|Jul precipitation mm = 221.5\n|Aug precipitation mm = 248.4\n|Sep precipitation mm = 160.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 41.8\n|Nov precipitation mm = 38.8\n|Dec precipitation mm = 37.5\n|Jan humidity = 69\n|Feb humidity = 74\n|Mar humidity = 78\n|Apr humidity = 80\n|May humidity = 80\n|Jun humidity = 82\n|Jul humidity = 79\n|Aug humidity = 80\n|Sep humidity = 75\n|Oct humidity = 66\n|Nov humidity = 65\n|Dec humidity = 65\n|unit rain days = 0.1 mm\n|Jan rain days =  8.0\n|Feb rain days = 12.5\n|Mar rain days = 16.4\n|Apr rain days = 17.8\n|May rain days = 20.1\n|Jun rain days = 19.5\n|Jul rain days = 16.7\n|Aug rain days = 17.8\n|Sep rain days = 12.6\n|Oct rain days =  6.1\n|Nov rain days =  5.3\n|Dec rain days =  5.8\n|Jan sun = 135.8 |Jan percentsun = 41\n|Feb sun =  91.7 |Feb percentsun = 29\n|Mar sun =  85.3 |Mar percentsun = 23\n|Apr sun =  92.8 |Apr percentsun = 24\n|May sun = 122.5 |May percentsun = 30\n|Jun sun = 155.3 |Jun percentsun = 38\n|Jul sun = 219.0 |Jul percentsun = 53\n|Aug sun = 200.9 |Aug percentsun = 50\n|Sep sun = 189.7 |Sep percentsun = 52\n|Oct sun = 197.1 |Oct percentsun = 55\n|Nov sun = 180.5 |Nov percentsun = 55\n|Dec sun = 172.0 |Dec percentsun = 52\n|source 1 = [http://data.cma.cn/data/weatherBk.html China Meteorological Data Service Center]\n|source 2 = [http://old-cdc.cma.gov.cn/shuju/search1.jsp China Meteorological Administration](precipitation days, sunshine hours 1971-2000)\n}}\n\n== Geology ==\nThe city's museum boasts the Guinness World Record for the largest collection of dinosaur eggs, with 10,008 individual samples as of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-collection-of-dinosaur-eggs|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=5 August 2015|title=Largest collection of dinosaur eggs}}</ref> Dinosaur skeletons and fossilized footprints have also been found nearby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/11550057/Builders-find-dinosaur-eggs-in-paleontologists-paradise-in-China.html|title=Builders find dinosaur eggs in paleontologist's paradise in China|author=Tom Phillips|work=Daily Telegraph|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Findings ===\nA dinosaur egg fossil dated back to the Late [[Cretaceous]] was discovered by primary school student named Zhang Yangzhe while playing near the [[Dong River (China)|Dong River]] in 2019 in July. The boy's mother, Li Xiaofang, later contacted the Heyuan Dinosaur Museum members, and under their excavation guidance more than 10 dinosaur egg fossils each about 9 centimeters in diameter and dating back to 66 million years were revealed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201907/26/WS5d3ac1b9a310d830564013c6.html|title=Boy finds 66-million-year-old dinosaur eggs - Chinadaily.com.cn|last=\u6c5f\u5dcd|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archaeology-world.com/chinese-boy-accidentally-finds-66-million-year-old-dinosaur-eggs/|title=Chinese Boy Accidentally Finds 66-Million-Year-Old Dinosaur Eggs {{!}} ARCHAEOLOGY WORLD|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mp.weixin.qq.com/s?__biz=MjM5MTA4NzgxNA==&mid=2651205545&idx=3&sn=dab82422bb5676931e8575547ff545a9&chksm=bd4862008a3feb1670ccdd575e27787eaa7da66ad56b717cffe35513199379e36c54f888e89d#rd|title=\u6cb3\u6e90\u53c8\u73b0\u6050\u9f99\u86cb\u5316\u77f3\uff0c\u662f\u7537\u5b69\u6c5f\u8fb9\u6e38\u73a9\u53d1\u73b0\uff01\u7f51\u53cb\uff1a\u4e0d\u53ef\u601d\u8bae|last=\u7f57\u5e0c|first=\u5218\u5fd7\u68e0|website=\u5fae\u4fe1\u516c\u4f17\u5e73\u53f0|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Language ==\nIn the great majority of Heyuan areas, [[Hakka Chinese]] is in general use.\n\nIn the greater part of areas in the city, Dongyuan County, Lianping County, Heping County, Longchuan County etc., it belongs to the Yuezhong dialect group, while in Zijin County and part of Longchuan County, it belongs to the Yuetai dialect group.\n\nAlso, in some areas on the banks of the [[Dongjiang]], [[Dongjiang Bendihua]] is in general use. Its classification is disputed between the Yuezhong division of Hakka and the Huihe division of Yue.\n\n== Administration ==\n[[File:Txu-oclc-10552568-nf50-1.jpg|thumb|Map of Heyuan (labeled as HO-Y\u00dcAN (HOY\u00dcN) (Walled) {{lang|zh|\u6cb3\u6e90}}) and surrounding region ([[Army Map Service|AMS]], 1954)]]\nHeyuan City administers Yuancheng District, Dongyuan County, Heping County, Longchuan County, Zijin County and Lianping County. The total area is {{convert|15,800|km\u00b2}}. Heyuan city and its districts have a population of 3.2194 million. The municipality seat is in Yuancheng District.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n!colspan=\"6\"| Map\n! Name\n! Simplified Chinese\n! Hanyu Pinyin\n! Population<br/>{{nowrap|(2010 census)}}\n! Area<br/>(km<sup>2</sup>)\n! Density<br/>(/km<sup>2</sup>)\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"6\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Heyuan.png|width=450|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=170|y=620|scale=450/750|text=[[Xinfengjiang Reservoir|''Wanl\u00fc<br>Lake'']]}}\n{{Image label|x=160|y=680|scale=450/750|text=[[Yuancheng District|'''Yuancheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=400|y=740|scale=450/750|text=[[Zijin County|'''Zijin<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=600|y=300|scale=450/750|text=[[Longchuan County, Guangdong|'''Longchuan<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=110|y=250|scale=450/750|text=[[Lianping County|'''Lianping<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=400|y=230|scale=450/750|text=[[Heping County|'''Heping<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=280|y=510|scale=450/750|text=[[Dongyuan County|'''Dongyuan<br>County''']]}}\n</div>\n|[[Yuancheng District]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u6e90\u57ce\u533a}}\n|Yu\u00e1nch\u00e9ng Q\u016b\n|463,907\n|361.47\n|1,283\n|-\n|[[Zijin County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u7d2b\u91d1\u53bf}}\n|Z\u01d0j\u012bn Xi\u00e0n\n|640,133\n|3,635.13\n|225\n|-\n|[[Longchuan County, Guangdong|Longchuan County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u9f99\u5ddd\u53bf}}\n|L\u00f3ngchu\u0101n Xi\u00e0n\n|694,480\n|3,081.31\n|225\n|-\n|[[Lianping County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u8fde\u5e73\u53bf}}\n|Li\u00e1np\u00edng Xi\u00e0n\n|337,002\n|2,275.08\n|148\n|-\n|[[Heping County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u548c\u5e73\u53bf}}\n|H\u00e9p\u00edng Xi\u00e0n\n|374,709\n|2,291.45\n|164\n|-\n|[[Dongyuan County]]\n|{{lang|zh-hans|\u4e1c\u6e90\u53bf}}\n|D\u014dngyu\u00e1n Xi\u00e0n\n|439,964\n|4,009.17\n|110\n|}\n\n== Economy ==\nHeyuan city is a major economic and transportation hub for the Beijing-Kowloon Railway and the Guangzhou-Meizhou-Shantou Railway which crosses the city. There is also a marshalling station at Longchuan, which is the biggest in southern China.\n\nState Highway 105 and 205 run through the city.  Dong River which Heyuan City is located in plays an important strategic waterway which allows huge cargo ships to transport goods to Huizhou, Dongguan, and Guangzhou.\n\nHeyuan city is the major producer of Chinese kiwi fruit dried mushrooms of Jiulian, garlic, Hakka brewed liquor, Xinfengjiang pure water and mineral water, bamboo mats, sweet tangerines, green tea, and pot culture.\n\n== Transport ==\nHeyuan is served by the [[Hong Kong]]-[[Beijing]] [[Jingjiu railway]] with two stations: [[Heyuan railway station]] and [[Longchuan railway station]].\n\n== Attractions ==\n[[File:Heyuan Guifeng Ta 2015.11.12 12-28-46.jpg|thumbnail|Guifeng Pagoda]]\n\n=== Xinfengjiang Forest Park ===\n{{further|Xinfengjiang Reservoir}}\nHeyuan City has a number of tourist attractions. There is a tall fountain located in Xinfengjiang forest park. There are scenic areas such as the Dagui Mountain and the first big artificial lake; Wanlu Lake and the Sujiawei Round House.\n\n=== Longchuan County ===\nLongchuan county is home to scenic spots in Huoshan and Shuikeng.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n=== Lianping ===\nThe Neiguan Mountains and rivers are located in Lianping county.\n\n=== Dongyuan County ===\nIn Dongyuan county, there are scenic spots at Huanglong Crag and Zhangxi.\n\n== Sister cities ==\n*{{flagdeco|Malaysia}} [[Kota Kinabalu]], Sabah, Malaysia\n*{{flagdeco|PRC}} [[Tieling]], [[Liaoning]], People's Republic of China\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Heyuan}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20111103110304/http://www.heyuan.gov.cn/website/index.jsp {{in lang|zh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120303155220/http://en.visitgd.com/overview/history/202877.shtml The history of Heyuan]\n\n{{Guangdong topics}}\n{{Guangdong}}\n{{Major cities along the Pearl River}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Guangdong]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref work: script-title, quote, zh in Publisher, etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heyuan"}
{"title_page": "Giant Bicycles", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Giant Manufacturing Co. Ltd.\n| logo = Giant logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{TSE|9921}}\n| founder = [[King Liu]]\n| industry = [[Bicycle|Bicycle manufacturing]]\n| products = [[Bicycle]]s\n| production = 6.6 million (2014)<ref name=\"cips\"/>\n| revenue = US$1.9 billion (2017)<ref name=\"cips\"/>\n| foundation = Dajia, Taichung, [[Taiwan]], 1972\n| location_city = [[Dajia District|Dajia]], [[Taichung]], [[Taiwan]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.giant-bicycles.com/}}\n}}\n{{Chinese|title=Giant Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|name1=Giant Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|t=\u5de8\u5927\u6a5f\u68b0\u5de5\u696d\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|s=\u5de8\u5927\u673a\u68b0\u5de5\u4e1a\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|l=Giant Industrial Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|p=j\u00f9d\u00e0 j\u012bxi\u00e8 g\u014dngy\u00e8 g\u01d4f\u00e8n y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n g\u014dngs\u012b|bpmf=\u3110\u3129\u02cb \u3109\u311a\u02cb \u3110\u3127 \u3112\u3127\u311d\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u3125 \u3127\u311d\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u02c7 \u3108\u3123\u02cb \u3127\u3121\u02c7 \u3112\u3127\u3122\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u3125 \u3119|altname=Giant|c2=\u6377\u5b89\u7279|l2=Giant (phonetic transcription)|p2=ji\u00e9 \u0101n t\u00e8|bpmf2=\u3110\u3127\u311d\u02ca \u3122 \u310a\u311c\u02cb}}\n\n[[File:Giant head badge 2.JPG|thumb|A Giant [[head badge]]]]\n[[File:Giant Cadex 980C bicycle.jpg|thumb|Giant Cadex 980C first mass-produced carbon fibre road bicycle]]\n[[File:Giant TCX Cyclocross.JPG|thumb|A Giant TCX Cyclocross]]\n\n'''Giant Manufacturing Co. Ltd.''' (commonly known as '''Giant''') is a Taiwanese [[bicycle]] manufacturer that is recognized as the world's largest bicycle manufacturer.<ref name=\"cips\">{{cite web|last1=Ratcliffe|first1=Alison|title=\u2018Secret\u2019 Giant is world\u2019s biggest bicycle manufacturer and still growing|url=https://www.cips.org/supply-management/news/2016/january/secret-giant-is-worlds-biggest-bicycle-manufacturer-and-still-growing/|website=Supply Management|publisher=Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> Giant has manufacturing facilities in [[Taiwan]], the [[Netherlands]], and [[China]].\n\n==History==\nGiant was established in 1972 in [[Dajia District|Dajia]], [[Taichung County]] in the nation of Taiwan (now part of [[Taichung City]]), by [[King Liu]] and several friends.{{who|date=December 2014}} A major breakthrough came in 1977 when Giant's chief executive, Tony Lo, negotiated a deal with [[Schwinn]] to begin manufacturing bikes as an [[Original equipment manufacturer|OEM]], manufacturing bicycles to be sold exclusively under other brand names as a [[private label]]. As bike sales increased in the U.S., and after workers at the Schwinn plant in Chicago went on strike in 1980, Giant became a key supplier, making more than two-thirds of Schwinn bikes by the mid-1980s, representing 75% of Giant's sales. When Schwinn decided to find a new source and in 1987 signed a contract with the China Bicycle Company to produce bikes in [[Shenzhen]], Giant, under new president Bill Austin (formerly vice-president marketing at Schwinn), established its own brand of bicycles to compete in the rapidly expanding $200-and-above price range. In 1984, Giant also set up a [[joint venture]], \"Giant Europe,\" with Andries Gaastra of Dutch bicycle manufacturer [[Koga-Miyata]].<ref>[http://www.vakantiefietser.nl/px/pers/gaastra.pdf Interview with Andries Gaastra (Dutch)]</ref> In 1992, Gaastra sold his shares back, and Giant became a full shareholder of Giant Europe.\n\nBy 2018, Giant had sales in over 50 countries, in more than 12,000<ref name=\"Giant\">{{cite web |url=http://www.giant-bicycles.com/en-us/aboutgiant |website=Giant Bicycles.com| title=About Giant}}</ref> retail stores. Its total annual sales in 2017 reached 6.6 million bicycles with revenue of US$1.9 billion.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bicycleretailer.com/international/2018/03/27/giant-posts-revenue-decline-2017-predicts-single-digit-growth-2018#.W6kuwy-ZNBw|title=Giant posts revenue decline for 2017, predicts single-digit growth for 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2018-09-24}}\n</ref>\n\n== Sub-brands ==\nIn 1996, Giant established their [[Mosh BMX]] division with the help of [[Redline Bicycles]] founder Linn Kastan and racer Jason Richardson. Mosh manufactured BMX bikes and parts, as well as managed a professional BMX racing team.<ref>{{cite web |title=MOSH BMX COMPANY |url=http://www.23mag.com/com/mosh/mosh.htm |website=www.23mag.com |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 2008, Mosh was disbanded.<ref>{{cite web |last1=de Jong |first1=Bart |title=FAT Friday week 49 |url=https://fatbmx.com/bmx-news/item/6037-fat-friday-week-49 |website=FatBMX |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en-gb |date=December 5, 2008}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008 Giant launched the Liv/Giant sub-brand with products focused exclusively on the female cycling market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ddg.com.tw/en/archives/work/liv|title=Rebrand brings breakthrough in female cycling market > Liv {{!}} DDG|website=www.ddg.com.tw|language=zh-TW|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> In 2014, the Liv/Giant sub-brand was re-branded to Liv.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/05/20/giant-relaunches-liv-stand-alone-women%E2%80%99s-brand#.W6vHbS-ZNBw|title=Giant relaunches Liv as stand-alone women\u2019s brand|work=Bicycle Retailer and Industry News|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref> The re-branding was meant to further differentiate the Liv brand products with existing Giant product, communicating the concept of \"designed by women for women\". All Liv products are designed from the ground up including frame geometry, carbon layup and utilizes separate molds and designs that separate it from Giant branded products. As part of the rebranding, dedicated Liv stores and Liv zones within most Giant retailers were introduced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/05/20/giant-relaunches-liv-stand-alone-women%E2%80%99s-brand#.WnLefqiWaiM|title=Giant relaunches Liv as stand-alone women\u2019s brand|work=Bicycle Retailer and Industry News|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> In 2015, Giant announced the global launch of its Momentum brand lifestyle bikes. The first two models, the iNeed Street and iWant Park, had an ARP of US$425 and were aimed at a younger, more urban demographic than Giant's more expensive performance road and mountain bikes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sgbonline.com/giant-launches-momentum-lifestyle-bikes/|title=Giant Launches Momentum Lifestyle Bikes {{!}} SGB Online|website=sgbonline.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Giant launched Cadex, previously the name of their mass-produced carbon fiber bicycle launched in 1987, as their line of bicycle components, wheels, tires and finishing kits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/giant-launches-cadex-wheels-and-finishing-kit-at-tour-de-france/|title=Giant launches Cadex wheels and finishing kit at Tour de France|last=Evans|first=Josh|date=5 July 2019|website=Cycling News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 September 2019}}</ref> Before the brand was officially launched, UCI WorldTeam teams sponsored by Giant (Team Sunweb on 2018, and CCC Pro Team on 2019) were seen with components branded as #Overachieve, which Giant says were race-tested prototypes of the Cadex components.\n\n==Technologies and innovations==\n[[File:Halfway-folded-unfolded.jpg|thumb|Giant Halfway folding bicycle]]\n[[File:Giant bike that Alexander Vinokourov used 20060203.jpg|thumb|right|The bike that [[Alexander Vinokourov]] used at the [[2005 Tour de France]]]]\n\nIn 1995, Giant designed the first road bicycle with a sloping top tube featuring a smaller rear triangle. The tighter chainstay-seatstay configuration is said to be inherently stiffer than a more conventional frame design, and because less material is used, the Compact Road design is also said to be lighter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/latest-news/icons-of-cycling-giant-tcr-206346|title=Icons of cycling: Giant TCR - Cycling Weekly|date=2016-01-15|work=Cycling Weekly|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> With more responsive cornering and improved acceleration, as well as improved aerodynamics, the Giant design became largely imitated.\n\nBy 1998, with [[Mike Burrows]], Giant refined the design for racing by the professional [[ONCE (cycling team)|ONCE team]]. This was only after initial resistance by the [[Union Cycliste Internationale]] and subsequent amendment to its regulations to allow for bicycles with a sloping top tube.\n\nGiant road frames were originally made of [[6061 aluminium alloy|6061 (ALUXX) aluminium alloy]] and were also characterised by bladed forks and seatposts to reduce air resistance. Frames came in three sizes (small, medium, and large), with riders fitted through the use of stems and seatposts of different lengths. By 2018, Giant road frames were available in up to six sizes (X-Small, Small, Medium, Medium/Large, Large and X-Large).\n\nIn 2003, the TCR frame was offered in carbon fibre construction and marketed as the TCR Composite range. In 2006, Giant added a higher-grade carbon fibre frame marketed as the TCR Advanced frame, which was characterised by an integrated seatpost (ISP). These frames were most notably raced at the Tour de France by T-Mobile's professional team. Using this design, the seatpost on the new frame must be cut precisely to fit the owner by a trained Giant dealer. The TCR Advanced SL frames with ISP continued to be raced internationally, most notably by the Rabobank team (2009-2013), Team Giant-Shimano (2014), Giant-Alpecin (2015\u20132016) and Team Sunweb (2017-2018).\n\nIn terms of other innovations, Giant also introduced its Maestro suspension in 2006. [https://web.archive.org/web/20151221164710/http://www.giant-bicycles.com/en-us/bike-catalogue/series-for-block/x-road/?block_id=9 Maestro Suspension], according to Giant, is designed to deliver an efficient rear suspension power transfer. Maestro utilizes a setup of four pivot points and two linkages to create a floating pivot point that is designed to reduce pedal bob and enables the rear wheel to travel vertically.\n\nAs of 2018, Giant categorizes its bicycles by user:\n* On-Road\n* X-Road \n* Off-Road\n* E-bikes\n* Youth\n\nWithin each Level are several Uses, such as Race, Endurance, City, Cruiser, etc.\n\nIn late 2016, Giant announced the ''Road-E+'' [[e-Bike]], which features:\n* HCT (Hybrid Cycling Technology) drive system\n* 500 watt 80Nm [[Yamaha]] mid drive motor\n* 400Wh or 500Wh EnergyPack integrated frame battery\n* PedalPlus 4-sensor technology, and \n* RideControl display & control pad with [[Bluetooth]] integration.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://electricbikereview.com/giant/road-e-plus/ |title=Giant Road-E+ Review |last= |first= |date= |website=EBR |publisher=Electric Bike Review |access-date=25 July 2017 |quote=}}\n</ref>\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Mashhad Samen Velodrome (2).jpg|200px|thumbnail|right|Giant banners in [[Mashhad Samen Velodrome]]]]\nGiant's first foray into professional road cycling was with the defunct [[ONCE (cycling team)|Spanish Team ONCE]] directed by [[Manolo Saiz]] using Giant TCR frames in custom sizes for each individual rider. [[Laurent Jalabert]] was one of the most notable cyclists in the ONCE Team.\n\nGiant currently sponsors a number of cycling teams as well as individual athletes.\n\nIn [[Road bicycle racing|road cycling]], Giant celebrated multiple achievements as the bike supplier of [[UCI WorldTeam]] Team Sunweb (both [[Team Sunweb (men's team)|men]] and [[Team Sunweb (women's team)|women]]), which competes in the highest level of road cycling. They are most noted for when both men and women teams won the [[Team time trial|Team Time Trial]] event at the [[2017 UCI World Championships]] in [[Bergen]], Norway. Notable riders include [[Tom Dumoulin]], winner of the pink jersey in the [[2017 Giro d'Italia]]; [[Warren Barguil]], winner of the polka-dot jersey in the [[2017 Tour de France]], and [[Michael Matthews (cyclist)|Michael Mathews]], winner of the green jersey in the 2017 Tour de France.\n\nIn 2019, Giant switched sponsorship from Team Sunweb to [[CCC Pro Team]].\n\nIn [[Mountain biking|off-road cycling]], Giant sponsors the Giant Factory Off-Road Team. Cyclists include [[Marcelo Gutierrez]], 5 time Colombian [[Downhill mountain biking|downhill]] national champion, and [[Jacob Dickson]], 4 time Irish junior downhill champion.\n\nGiant also sponsors individual athletes, including [[Tim Berkel|Tim van Berkel]], [[Ben Dijkstra]], and [[Matthew Bottrill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.giant-bicycles.com/gb/teams-and-riders|title= Teams and Riders, Great Britain |website=Giant Bicycles.com|access-date=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of companies of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Giant Manufacturing}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.giant-bicycles.com/}}\n\n{{Folding bicycles}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle manufacturers of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Taiwan Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Mountain bike manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese brands]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Taiwan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Giant Manufacturing Co. Ltd.\n| logo = Giant logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{TSE|9921}}\n| founder = [[King Liu]]\n| industry = [[Bicycle|Bicycle manufacturing]]\n| products = [[Bicycle]]s\n| production = 6.6 million (2014)<ref name=\"cips\"/>\n| revenue = US$1.9 billion (2017)<ref name=\"cips\"/>\n| foundation = Dajia, Taichung, [[Taiwan]], 1972\n| location_city = [[Dajia District|Dajia]], [[Taichung]], [[Taiwan]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.giant-bicycles.com/}}\n}}\n{{Chinese|title=Giant Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|name1=Giant Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|t=\u5de8\u5927\u6a5f\u68b0\u5de5\u696d\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|s=\u5de8\u5927\u673a\u68b0\u5de5\u4e1a\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|l=Giant Industrial Manufacturing Co., Ltd.|p=j\u00f9d\u00e0 j\u012bxi\u00e8 g\u014dngy\u00e8 g\u01d4f\u00e8n y\u01d2uxi\u00e0n g\u014dngs\u012b|bpmf=\u3110\u3129\u02cb \u3109\u311a\u02cb \u3110\u3127 \u3112\u3127\u311d\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u3125 \u3127\u311d\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u02c7 \u3108\u3123\u02cb \u3127\u3121\u02c7 \u3112\u3127\u3122\u02cb \u310d\u3128\u3125 \u3119|altname=Giant|c2=\u6377\u5b89\u7279|l2=Giant (phonetic transcription)|p2=ji\u00e9 \u0101n t\u00e8|bpmf2=\u3110\u3127\u311d\u02ca \u3122 \u310a\u311c\u02cb}}\n\n[[File:Giant head badge 2.JPG|thumb|A Giant [[head badge]]]]\n[[File:Giant Cadex 980C bicycle.jpg|thumb|Giant Cadex 980C first mass-produced carbon fibre road bicycle]]\n[[File:Giant TCX Cyclocross.JPG|thumb|A Giant TCX Cyclocross]]\n\n'''Giant Manufacturing Co. Ltd.''' (commonly known as '''Giant''') is a Taiwanese [[bicycle]] manufacturer that is recognized as the world's largest bicycle manufacturer.<ref name=\"cips\">{{cite web|last1=Ratcliffe|first1=Alison|title=\u2018Secret\u2019 Giant is world\u2019s biggest bicycle manufacturer and still growing|url=https://www.cips.org/supply-management/news/2016/january/secret-giant-is-worlds-biggest-bicycle-manufacturer-and-still-growing/|website=Supply Management|publisher=Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> Giant has manufacturing facilities in [[Taiwan]], the [[Netherlands]], and [[China]].\n\n==History==\nGiant was established in 1972 in [[Dajia District|Dajia]], [[Taichung County]] in the nation of Taiwan (now part of [[Taichung City]]), by [[King Liu]] and several friends.{{who|date=December 2014}} A major breakthrough came in 1977 when Giant\u2019s chief executive, Tony Lo, negotiated a deal with [[Schwinn]] to begin manufacturing bikes as an [[Original equipment manufacturer|OEM]], manufacturing bicycles to be sold exclusively under other brand names as a [[private label]]. As bike sales increased in the U.S., and after workers at the Schwinn plant in Chicago went on strike in 1980, Giant became a key supplier, making more than two-thirds of Schwinn bikes by the mid-1980s, representing 75% of Giant\u2019s sales. When Schwinn decided to find a new source and in 1987 signed a contract with the China Bicycle Company to produce bikes in [[Shenzhen]], Giant, under new president Bill Austin (formerly vice-president marketing at Schwinn), established its own brand of bicycles to compete in the rapidly expanding $200-and-above price range. In 1984, Giant also set up a [[joint venture]], \"Giant Europe,\" with Andries Gaastra of Dutch bicycle manufacturer [[Koga-Miyata]].<ref>[http://www.vakantiefietser.nl/px/pers/gaastra.pdf Interview with Andries Gaastra (Dutch)]</ref> In 1992, Gaastra sold his shares back, and Giant became a full shareholder of Giant Europe.\n\nBy 2018, Giant had sales in over 50 countries, in more than 12,000<ref name=\"Giant\">{{cite web |url=http://www.giant-bicycles.com/en-us/aboutgiant |website=Giant Bicycles.com| title=About Giant}}</ref> retail stores. Its total annual sales in 2017 reached 6.6 million bicycles with revenue of US$1.9 billion.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bicycleretailer.com/international/2018/03/27/giant-posts-revenue-decline-2017-predicts-single-digit-growth-2018#.W6kuwy-ZNBw|title=Giant posts revenue decline for 2017, predicts single-digit growth for 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2018-09-24}}\n</ref>\n\n== Sub-brands ==\nIn 1996, Giant established their [[Mosh BMX]] division with the help of [[Redline Bicycles]] founder Linn Kastan and racer Jason Richardson. Mosh manufactured BMX bikes and parts, as well as managed a professional BMX racing team.<ref>{{cite web |title=MOSH BMX COMPANY |url=http://www.23mag.com/com/mosh/mosh.htm |website=www.23mag.com |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 2008, Mosh was disbanded.<ref>{{cite web |last1=de Jong |first1=Bart |title=FAT Friday week 49 |url=https://fatbmx.com/bmx-news/item/6037-fat-friday-week-49 |website=FatBMX |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en-gb |date=December 5, 2008}}</ref> \n\nIn 2008 Giant launched the Liv/Giant sub-brand with products focused exclusively on the female cycling market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ddg.com.tw/en/archives/work/liv|title=Rebrand brings breakthrough in female cycling market > Liv {{!}} DDG|website=www.ddg.com.tw|language=zh-TW|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> In 2014, the Liv/Giant sub-brand was re-branded to Liv.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/05/20/giant-relaunches-liv-stand-alone-women%E2%80%99s-brand#.W6vHbS-ZNBw|title=Giant relaunches Liv as stand-alone women\u2019s brand|work=Bicycle Retailer and Industry News|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref> The re-branding was meant to further differentiate the Liv brand products with existing Giant product, communicating the concept of \"designed by women for women\". All Liv products are designed from the ground up including frame geometry, carbon layup and utilizes separate molds and designs that separate it from Giant branded products. As part of the rebranding, dedicated Liv stores and Liv zones within most Giant retailers were introduced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bicycleretailer.com/north-america/2014/05/20/giant-relaunches-liv-stand-alone-women%E2%80%99s-brand#.WnLefqiWaiM|title=Giant relaunches Liv as stand-alone women\u2019s brand|work=Bicycle Retailer and Industry News|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> In 2015, Giant announced the global launch of its Momentum brand lifestyle bikes. The first two models, the iNeed Street and iWant Park, had an ARP of US$425 and were aimed at a younger, more urban demographic than Giant's more expensive performance road and mountain bikes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sgbonline.com/giant-launches-momentum-lifestyle-bikes/|title=Giant Launches Momentum Lifestyle Bikes {{!}} SGB Online|website=sgbonline.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Giant launched Cadex, previously the name of their mass produced carbon fiber bicycle launched in 1987, as their line of bicycle components, wheels, tires and finishing kits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/giant-launches-cadex-wheels-and-finishing-kit-at-tour-de-france/|title=Giant launches Cadex wheels and finishing kit at Tour de France|last=Evans|first=Josh|date=5 July 2019|website=Cycling News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 September 2019}}</ref> Before the brand was officially launched, UCI WorldTeam teams sponsored by Giant (Team Sunweb on 2018, and CCC Pro Team on 2019) were seen with components branded as #Overachieve, which Giant says were race-tested prototypes of the Cadex components.\n\n==Technologies and innovations==\n[[File:Halfway-folded-unfolded.jpg|thumb|Giant Halfway folding bicycle]]\n[[File:Giant bike that Alexander Vinokourov used 20060203.jpg|thumb|right|The bike that [[Alexander Vinokourov]] used at the [[2005 Tour de France]]]]\n\nIn 1995, Giant designed the first road bicycle with a sloping top tube featuring a smaller rear triangle. The tighter chainstay-seatstay configuration is said to be inherently stiffer than a more conventional frame design, and because less material is used, the Compact Road design is also said to be lighter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/latest-news/icons-of-cycling-giant-tcr-206346|title=Icons of cycling: Giant TCR - Cycling Weekly|date=2016-01-15|work=Cycling Weekly|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref> With more responsive cornering and improved acceleration, as well as improved aerodynamics, the Giant design became largely imitated.\n\nBy 1998, with [[Mike Burrows]], Giant refined the design for racing by the professional [[ONCE (cycling team)|ONCE team]]. This was only after initial resistance by the [[Union Cycliste Internationale]] and subsequent amendment to its regulations to allow for bicycles with a sloping top tube.\n\nGiant road frames were originally made of [[6061 aluminium alloy|6061 (ALUXX) aluminium alloy]] and were also characterised by bladed forks and seatposts to reduce air resistance. Frames came in three sizes (small, medium, and large), with riders fitted through the use of stems and seatposts of different lengths. By 2018, Giant road frames were available in up to six sizes (X-Small, Small, Medium, Medium/Large, Large and X-Large).\n\nIn 2003, the TCR frame was offered in carbon fibre construction and marketed as the TCR Composite range. In 2006, Giant added a higher-grade carbon fibre frame marketed as the TCR Advanced frame, which was characterised by an integrated seatpost (ISP). These frames were most notably raced at the Tour de France by T-Mobile's professional team. Using this design, the seatpost on the new frame must be cut precisely to fit the owner by a trained Giant dealer. The TCR Advanced SL frames with ISP continued to be raced internationally, most notably by the Rabobank team (2009-2013), Team Giant-Shimano (2014), Giant-Alpecin (2015\u20132016) and Team Sunweb (2017-2018).\n\nIn terms of other innovations, Giant also introduced its Maestro suspension in 2006. [https://web.archive.org/web/20151221164710/http://www.giant-bicycles.com/en-us/bike-catalogue/series-for-block/x-road/?block_id=9 Maestro Suspension], according to Giant, is designed to deliver an efficient rear suspension power transfer. Maestro utilizes a setup of four pivot points and two linkages to create a floating pivot point that is designed to reduce pedal bob and enables the rear wheel to travel vertically.\n\nAs of 2018, Giant categorizes its bicycles by user:\n* On-Road\n* X-Road \n* Off-Road\n* E-bikes\n* Youth\n\nWithin each Level are several Uses, such as Race, Endurance, City, Cruiser, etc.\n\nIn late 2016, Giant announced the ''Road-E+'' [[e-Bike]], which features:\n* HCT (Hybrid Cycling Technology) drive system\n* 500 watt 80Nm [[Yamaha]] mid drive motor\n* 400Wh or 500Wh EnergyPack integrated frame battery\n* PedalPlus 4-sensor technology, and \n* RideControl display & control pad with [[Bluetooth]] integration.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://electricbikereview.com/giant/road-e-plus/ |title=Giant Road-E+ Review |last= |first= |date= |website=EBR |publisher=Electric Bike Review |access-date=25 July 2017 |quote=}}\n</ref>\n\n==Sponsorships==\n[[File:Mashhad Samen Velodrome (2).jpg|200px|thumbnail|right|Giant banners in [[Mashhad Samen Velodrome]]]]\nGiant's first foray into professional road cycling was with the defunct [[ONCE (cycling team)|Spanish Team ONCE]] directed by [[Manolo Saiz]] using Giant TCR frames in custom sizes for each individual rider. [[Laurent Jalabert]] was one of the most notable cyclists in the ONCE Team.\n\nGiant currently sponsors a number of cycling teams as well as individual athletes.\n\nIn [[Road bicycle racing|road cycling]], Giant celebrated multiple achievements as the bike supplier of [[UCI WorldTeam]] Team Sunweb (both [[Team Sunweb (men's team)|men]] and [[Team Sunweb (women's team)|women]]), which competes in the highest level of road cycling. They are most noted for when both men and women teams won the [[Team time trial|Team Time Trial]] event at the [[2017 UCI World Championships]] in [[Bergen]], Norway. Notable riders include [[Tom Dumoulin]], winner of the pink jersey in the [[2017 Giro d'Italia]]; [[Warren Barguil]], winner of the polka-dot jersey in the [[2017 Tour de France]], and [[Michael Matthews (cyclist)|Michael Mathews]], winner of the green jersey in the 2017 Tour de France.\n\nIn 2019, Giant switched sponsorship from Team Sunweb to [[CCC Pro Team]].\n\nIn [[Mountain biking|off-road cycling]], Giant sponsors the Giant Factory Off-Road Team. Cyclists include [[Marcelo Gutierrez]], 5 time Colombian [[Downhill mountain biking|downhill]] national champion, and [[Jacob Dickson]], 4 time Irish junior downhill champion.\n\nGiant also sponsors individual athletes, including [[Tim Berkel|Tim van Berkel]], [[Ben Dijkstra]], and [[Matthew Bottrill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.giant-bicycles.com/gb/teams-and-riders|title= Teams and Riders, Great Britain |website=Giant Bicycles.com|access-date=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of companies of Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Giant Manufacturing}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.giant-bicycles.com/}}\n\n{{Folding bicycles}}\n\n[[Category:Cycle manufacturers of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Taiwan Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Mountain bike manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese brands]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Taiwan]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: mass produced \u2192 mass-produced, \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giant_Bicycles"}
{"title_page": "Injective tensor product", "text_new": "The '''injective tensor product''' of two [[topological vector space]]s was introduced by [[Alexander Grothendieck]] and was used by him to define [[nuclear spaces]].\n\n==Preliminaries and notation==\nThroughout let ''X'',''Y'', and ''Z'' be [[topological vector space]]s and <math>L : X \\to Y</math> be a linear map. \n\n* <math>L : X \\to Y</math> is a '''topological homomorphism''' or '''homomorphism''', if it is linear, continuous, and <math>L : X \\to \\operatorname{Im} L</math> is an [[open map]], where <math>\\operatorname{Im} L</math>, the image of ''L'', has the subspace topology induced by ''Y''. \n** If ''S'' is a subspace of ''X'' then both the quotient map <math>X \\to X / S</math> and the canonical injection <math>S \\to X</math> are homomorphisms. In particular, any linear map <math>L : X \\to Y</math> can be canonically decomposed as follows: <math>X \\to X / \\operatorname{ker} L \\overset{L_0}{\\rightarrow} \\operatorname{Im} L \\to Y</math> where <math>L_0\\left( x + \\operatorname{ker} L \\right) := L (x)</math> defines a bijection. \n* The set of continuous linear maps <math>X \\to Z</math> (resp. continuous bilinear maps <math>X \\times Y \\to Z</math>) will be denoted by ''L(X, Z)'' (resp. ''B(X, Y; Z)'') where if ''Z'' is the scalar field then we may instead write ''L(X)'' (resp. ''B(X, Y)''). \n* The set of separately continuous bilinear maps <math>X \\times Y \\to Z</math> (i.e. continuous in each variable when the other variable is fixed) will be denoted by <math>\\mathcal{B}(X, Y; Z)</math> where if <math>Z</math> is the scalar field then we may instead write <math>\\mathcal{B}(X, Y)</math>. \n* We will denote the continuous dual space of ''X'' by X* or <math>X^{\\prime}</math> and the algebraic dual space (which is the vector space of all linear functionals on ''X'', whether continuous or not) by <math>X^{\\#}</math>. \n** To increase the clarity of the exposition, we use the common convention of writing elements of <math>X^{\\prime}</math> with a prime following the symbol (e.g. <math>x^{\\prime}</math> denotes an element of <math>X^{\\prime}</math> and not, say, a derivative and the variables ''x'' and <math>x^{\\prime}</math> need not be related in any way). \n\n=== Notation for topologies ===\n{{Main|Topology of uniform convergence|Mackey topology}}\n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X, X*)|\u03c3(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the [[coarsest topology]] on ''X'' making every map in X\u2032 continuous and <math>X_{\\sigma\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or  <math>X_{\\sigma}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X, X*)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X*, X) or the weak* topology|\u03c3(X\u2032, X)]] denotes [[weak-* topology]] on X* and <math>X_{\\sigma\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or  <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X\u2032, X) or the weak* topology|X\u2032 endowed with this topology]]. \n** Note that every <math>x_0 \\in X</math> induces a map <math>X^{\\prime} \\to \\mathbb{R}</math> defined by <math>\\lambda \\mapsto \\lambda \\left( x_0 \\right)</math>. \u03c3(X\u2032, X) is the coarsest topology on X\u2032 making all such maps continuous.\n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Bounded convergence b(X, X*)|b(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''topology of bounded convergence on ''X''''' and <math>X_{b\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or <math>X_{b}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Bounded convergence b(X, X*)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Strong dual topology b(X*, X)|b(X\u2032, X)]] denotes the '''topology of bounded convergence on X\u2032''' or the '''strong dual topology on X\u2032''' and <math>X_{b\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or <math>X^{\\prime}_{b}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Strong dual topology b(X*, X)|X\u2032 endowed with this topology]]. \n** As usual, if X* is considered as a topological vector space but it has not been made clear what topology it is endowed with, then the topology will be assumed to be b(X\u2032, X). \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X, X*)|\ud835\udf0f(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''[[Mackey topology]]''' on ''X'' or the '''[[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X, X*)|topology of uniform convergence on the convex balanced weakly compact subsets of ''X\u2032'']]''' and <math>X_{\\tau\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or <math>X_{\\tau}</math> denotes ''X'' endowed with this topology. <math>\\tau(X, X^{\\prime})</math> is the finest locally convex TVS topology on ''X'' whose continuous dual space is equal to <math>X^{\\prime}</math>. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X*, X)|\ud835\udf0f(X\u2032, X)]] denotes the '''[[Mackey topology]]''' on ''X\u2032'' or the '''[[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X*, X)|topology of uniform convergence on the convex balanced weakly compact subsets of ''X'']]''' and <math>X_{\\tau\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or  <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}</math> denotes ''X'' endowed with this topology. \n** Note that <math>\\tau\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right) \\subseteq b\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right) \\subseteq \\tau \\left( X^{\\prime}, X^{\\prime\\prime} \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=432-434}} \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Convergence on equicontinuous sets \u03b5(X, X*)|\u03b5(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''topology of uniform convergence on equicontinuous subsets of X\u2032''' and <math>X_{\\epsilon\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or  <math>X_{\\epsilon}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Convergence on equicontinuous sets \u03b5(X, X\u2032)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n** If ''H'' is a set of linear mappings <math>X \\to Y</math> then ''H'' is [[equicontinuous]] if and only if it is equicontinuous at the origin; that is, if and only if for every neighborhood ''V'' of ''0'' in ''Y'', there exists a neighborhood ''U'' of ''0'' in ''X'' such that <math>\\lambda (U) \\subseteq V</math> for every <math>\\lambda \\in H</math>.\n\n== Definition ==\nThroughout let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[topological vector space]]s with continuous dual spaces <math>X^*</math> and <math>Y^*</math>. Note that almost all results described are independent of whether these vector spaces are over <math>\\mathbb{R}</math> or <math>\\mathbb{C}</math> but to simplify the exposition we will assume that they are over the field <math>\\mathbb{C}</math>. \n\n=== Continuous bilinear maps as a tensor product ===\nNote that the question of whether or not one vector space is a [[tensor product]] of two other vector spaces is a purely algebraic one (i.e. the answer does not depend on the topologies of ''X'' or ''Y''). Nevertheless, the vector space <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> of continuous bilinear functionals is always a tensor product of ''X'' and ''Y'', as we now describe. \n\nFor every <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> we now define bilinear form, denoted by the symbol ''x \u2297 y'', from <math>X^{\\prime} \\times Y^{\\prime}</math> into the underlying field (i.e. <math>x \\otimes y : X^{\\prime} \\times Y^{\\prime} \\to \\mathbb{C}</math>) by \n: <math>\\left(x \\otimes y\\right) \\left(x^{\\prime}, y^{\\prime} \\right) := x^{\\prime}(x) y^{\\prime}(y)</math>. \nThis induces a canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to \\mathcal{B}\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> defined by sending <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> to the bilinear form <math>x \\otimes y</math>. \nThe span of the range of this map is <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math>. \nThe following theorem may be used to verify that <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> together with the above map \u2297 is a tensor product of ''X'' and ''Y''. \n\n'''Theorem''' Let ''X'', ''Y'', and ''Z'' be vector spaces and let <math>T : X \\times Y \\to Z</math> be a bilinear map. Then the following are equivalent:{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=403-404}} \n# ''(Z, T)'' is a [[tensor product]] of ''X'' and ''Y'';\n# (a) the image of ''T'' spans all of ''Z'', and (b) ''X'' and ''Y'' are ''T''-linearly disjoint (this means that for all positive integers ''n'' and all elements <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_n \\in X</math> and <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n \\in Y</math> such that <math>\\sum_{i=1}^{n} T(x_i, y_i) = 0</math>, (i) if all <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_n</math> are linearly independent then all <math>y_i</math> are 0, and (ii) if all <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n</math> are linearly independent then all <math>x_i</math> are 0).\n:* Equivalently, ''X'' and ''Y'' are ''T''-linearly disjoint if and only if for all linearly independent sequences <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_m</math> in ''X'' and all linearly independent sequences <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n</math> in ''Y'', the vectors <math>\\left\\{ T(x_i, y_j) : 1 \\leq i \\leq m, 1 \\leq j \\leq n \\right\\}</math> are linearly independent.\n\n=== Topology ===\n\nHenceforth, all topological vector spaces considered will be assumed to be locally convex. \nIf ''Z'' is any locally convex topological vector space, then for any [[equicontinuous]] subsets <math>G \\subseteq X^{\\prime}</math> and <math>H \\subseteq Y^{\\prime}</math>, and any neighborhood <math>N</math> in ''Z'', define \n:<math>\\mathcal{U}(G, H, N) = \\{b \\in \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right) : b(G, H) \\subseteq N\\}</math>\nIt can be shown that every set <math>b(G, H)</math> is bounded, which is necessary and sufficient for the collection of all such <math>\\mathcal{U}(G, H, N)</math> to form a locally convex TVS topology on <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> called the '''\u03b5-topology'''. When <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> (resp. <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, etc.) is endowed with the \u03b5-topology, it will be denoted by <math>\\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> (resp. <math>\\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, <math>B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, etc.). \n(Note that <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right) \\subseteq B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right) \\subseteq \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math>). \n\nIn particular, when ''Z'' is the underlying scalar field then since <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math>, we will denote <math>B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> by <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math>, which is called the '''injective tensor product''' of ''X'' and ''Y''. The space <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is not necessarily complete so we denote its completion by <math>X \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} Y</math>. The space <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is complete if and only if both ''X'' and ''Y'' are complete, in which case the completion of <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is a subvector space of <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math>.\n\n=== Canonical identification of separately continuous bilinear maps with linear maps ===\nOne may show that the set equality <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right) = L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math> holds (i.e. if <math>u : X^{\\prime} \\to Y</math> is a linear map, then <math>u : X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y_{\\sigma\\left( Y, Y^{\\prime} \\right)}</math> is continuous if and only if <math>u : X^{\\prime}_{\\tau\\left(X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y</math> is continuous, where here ''Y'' has it's original topology).{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}}   \n\nThere is also a canonical vector space isomorphism <math>J : \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( Y^{\\prime}, Y \\right)} \\right) \\to L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma \\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)}; Y_{\\sigma \\left( Y, Y^{\\prime} \\right)} \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}}  \nTo define it, for every separately continuous bilinear form <math>B</math> defined on <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\times Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( Y^{\\prime}, Y \\right)}</math> and every <math>x^{\\prime} \\in X^{\\prime}</math>, let <math>B_{x^{\\prime}} \\in \\left( Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)^{\\prime}</math> be defined by <math>B_{x^{\\prime}}\\left( y^{\\prime} \\right) := B\\left( x^{\\prime}, y^{\\prime} \\right)</math>. \nSince <math>\\left( Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)^{\\prime}</math> is canonically vector space-isomorphic to ''Y'' (via the canonical map <math>y \\mapsto </math> value at ''y''), we will identify <math>B_{x^{\\prime}}</math> as an element of ''Y'', which we'll denote by <math>\\tilde{B}_{x^{\\prime}} \\in Y</math>. \nThis defines a map <math>\\tilde{B} : X^{\\prime} \\to Y</math> given by <math>x^{\\prime} \\mapsto \\tilde{B}_{x^{\\prime}}</math> and so the canonical isomorphism is of course defined by <math>J(B) := \\tilde{B}</math>. \n\nWhen <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> is given the topology of uniform convergence on equicontinous subsets of ''X\u2032'', the canonical map becomes a TVS-isomorphism <math>J : \\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right) \\to L_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}} In particular, <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y = B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> can be canonically TVS-embedded into <math>L_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math>; furthermore the image in <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> of <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y = B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> under the canonical map ''J'' consists exactly of the space of continuous linear maps <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y</math> whose image is finite dimensional.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=432-433}}\n\n== Relation to projective tensor product and nuclear spaces ==\nThe [[strongest]] locally convex topology on <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math> making the canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> (defined by sending <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> to the bilinear form <math>x \\otimes y</math>) continuous is called the '''projective topology''' or the '''\u03c0-topology'''. When <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math> is endowed with this topology then it will be denoted by <math>X \\otimes_{\\pi} Y</math> and called the '''projective tensor product''' of ''X'' and ''Y''. \n\n\n== Canonical identifications of bilinear and linear maps ==\nIn this section we describe canonical identifications between spaces of bilinear and linear maps. These identifications will be used to define important subspaces and topologies (particularly those that relate to [[nuclear operator]]s and [[nuclear space]]s).\n\n== Properties ==\n\n* The canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to \\mathcal{B}\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> is continuous.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=434}} \n* If ''X'' and ''Y'' are normed then <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math> is normable. \n* <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math> is Hausdorff if and only if both ''X'' and ''Y'' are Hausdorff.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=434}}\n* Suppose that <math>u : X_1 \\to Y_1</math> and <math>v : X_2 \\to Y_2</math> are two linear maps between locally convex spaces. If both ''u'' and ''v'' are continuous then so is their tensor product <math>u \\otimes v : X_1 \\otimes_{\\epsilon} X_2 \\to Y_1 \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y_2</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=439}}\n** If ''u'' and ''v'' are both TVS-isomorphisms then so is <math>u \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} v : X_1 \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} X_2 \\to Y_1 \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} Y_2</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=440}}  \n* The \u03b5-topology is always finer than the [[Projective tensor product|\u03c0-topology]] and coarser than the [[inductive topology]] (which is the finest locally convex TVS topology making <math>X \\times Y \\to X \\otimes Y</math> separately continuous).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Final topology]]\n* [[Projective tensor product]]\n* [[Nuclear operator]]s\n* [[Nuclear space]]s\n* [[Topological tensor product]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book | last=Diestel | first=Joe | title=The metric theory of tensor products : Grothendieck's r\u00e9sum\u00e9 revisited | publisher=American Mathematical Society | publication-place=Providence, R.I | year=2008 | isbn=0-8218-4440-7 | oclc=185095773 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Diestel | 2008 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Dubinsky | first=Ed | title=The structure of nuclear Fr\u00e9chet spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1979 | isbn=3-540-09504-7 | oclc=5126156 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Dubinsky | 1979 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Grothendieck | first=Grothendieck | title=Produits tensoriels topologiques et espaces nucl\u00e9aires | publisher=American Mathematical Society | publication-place=Providence | year=1966 | isbn=0-8218-1216-5 | oclc=1315788 | language=fr | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Grothendieck | 1966 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Husain | first=Taqdir | title=Barrelledness in topological and ordered vector spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1978 | isbn=3-540-09096-7 | oclc=4493665 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Husain | 1978 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Khaleelulla | first=S. M. | title=Counterexamples in topological vector spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1982 | isbn=978-3-540-11565-6 | oclc=8588370 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Khaleelulla | 1982 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Nlend | first=H | title=Bornologies and functional analysis : introductory course on the theory of duality topology-bornology and its use in functional analysis | publisher=North-Holland Pub. Co. Sole distributors for the U.S.A. and Canada, Elsevier-North Holland | publication-place=Amsterdam New York New York | year=1977 | isbn=0-7204-0712-5 | oclc=2798822 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Nlend | 1977 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Nlend | first=H | title=Nuclear and conuclear spaces : introductory courses on nuclear and conuclear spaces in the light of the duality | publisher=North-Holland Pub. Co. Sole distributors for the U.S.A. and Canada, Elsevier North-Holland | publication-place=Amsterdam New York New York, N.Y | year=1981 | isbn=0-444-86207-2 | oclc=7553061 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Nlend | 1981 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Pietsch | first=Albrecht | title=Nuclear locally convex spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin,New York | year=1972 | isbn=0-387-05644-0 | oclc=539541 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Pietsch | 1972 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Robertson | first=A. P. | title=Topological vector spaces | publisher=University Press | publication-place=Cambridge England | year=1973 | isbn=0-521-29882-2 | oclc=589250 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Robertson | 1973 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Ryan | first=Raymond | title=Introduction to tensor products of Banach spaces | publisher=Springer | publication-place=London New York | year=2002 | isbn=1-85233-437-1 | oclc=48092184 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Ryan | 2002 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Schaefer | first=Helmut H.| title=Topological Vector Spaces | publisher=Springer New York Imprint Springer | series=[[Graduate Texts in Mathematics|GTM]] | volume=3 | publication-place=New York, NY | year=1999 | isbn=978-1-4612-7155-0 | oclc=840278135 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Schaefer | 1999 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Treves | first=Francois | title=Topological vector spaces, distributions and kernels | publisher=Dover Publications | publication-place=Mineola, N.Y | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-486-45352-1 | oclc=853623322 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | author=Wong | title=Schwartz spaces, nuclear spaces, and tensor products | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1979 | isbn=3-540-09513-6 | oclc=5126158 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Wong | 1979 | p=}} -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/nuclear+space Nuclear space at ncatlab]\n\n{{Template:Functional analysis}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n", "text_old": "The '''injective tensor product''' of two [[topological vector space]]s was introduced by [[Alexander Grothendieck]] and was used by him to define [[nuclear spaces]].\n\n==Preliminaries and notation==\nThroughout let ''X'',''Y'', and ''Z'' be [[topological vector space]]s and <math>L : X \\to Y</math> be a linear map. \n\n* <math>L : X \\to Y</math> is a '''topological homomorphism''' or '''homomorphism''', if it is linear, continuous, and <math>L : X \\to \\operatorname{Im} L</math> is an [[open map]], where <math>\\operatorname{Im} L</math>, the image of ''L'', has the subspace topology induced by ''Y''. \n** If ''S'' is a subspace of ''X'' then both the quotient map <math>X \\to X / S</math> and the canonical injection <math>S \\to X</math> are homomorphisms. In particular, any linear map <math>L : X \\to Y</math> can be canonically decomposed as follows: <math>X \\to X / \\operatorname{ker} L \\overset{L_0}{\\rightarrow} \\operatorname{Im} L \\to Y</math> where <math>L_0\\left( x + \\operatorname{ker} L \\right) := L (x)</math> defines a bijection. \n* The set of continuous linear maps <math>X \\to Z</math> (resp. continuous bilinear maps <math>X \\times Y \\to Z</math>) will be denoted by ''L(X, Z)'' (resp. ''B(X, Y; Z)'') where if ''Z'' is the scalar field then we may instead write ''L(X)'' (resp. ''B(X, Y)''). \n* The set of separately continuous bilinear maps <math>X \\times Y \\to Z</math> (i.e. continuous in each variable when the other variable is fixed) will be denoted by <math>\\mathcal{B}(X, Y; Z)</math> where if <math>Z</math> is the scalar field then we may instead write <math>\\mathcal{B}(X, Y)</math>. \n* We will denote the continuous dual space of ''X'' by X* or <math>X^{\\prime}</math> and the algebraic dual space (which is the vector space of all linear functionals on ''X'', whether continuous or not) by <math>X^{\\#}</math>. \n** To increase the clarity of the exposition, we use the common convention of writing elements of <math>X^{\\prime}</math> with a prime following the symbol (e.g. <math>x^{\\prime}</math> denotes an element of <math>X^{\\prime}</math> and not, say, a derivative and the variables ''x'' and <math>x^{\\prime}</math> need not be related in any way). \n\n=== Notation for topologies ===\n{{Main|Topology of uniform convergence|Mackey topology}}\n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X, X*)|\u03c3(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the [[coarsest topology]] on ''X'' making every map in X\u2032 continuous and <math>X_{\\sigma\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or  <math>X_{\\sigma}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X, X*)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X*, X) or the weak* topology|\u03c3(X\u2032, X)]] denotes [[weak-* topology]] on X* and <math>X_{\\sigma\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or  <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#The weak topology \u03c3(X\u2032, X) or the weak* topology|X\u2032 endowed with this topology]]. \n** Note that every <math>x_0 \\in X</math> induces a map <math>X^{\\prime} \\to \\mathbb{R}</math> defined by <math>\\lambda \\mapsto \\lambda \\left( x_0 \\right)</math>. \u03c3(X\u2032, X) is the coarsest topology on X\u2032 making all such maps continuous.\n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Bounded convergence b(X, X*)|b(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''topology of bounded convergence on ''X''''' and <math>X_{b\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or <math>X_{b}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Bounded convergence b(X, X*)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Strong dual topology b(X*, X)|b(X\u2032, X)]] denotes the '''topology of bounded convergence on X\u2032''' or the '''strong dual topology on X\u2032''' and <math>X_{b\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or <math>X^{\\prime}_{b}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Strong dual topology b(X*, X)|X\u2032 endowed with this topology]]. \n** As usual, if X* is considered as a topological vector space but it has not been made clear what topology it is endowed with, then the topology will be assumed to be b(X\u2032, X). \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X, X*)|\ud835\udf0f(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''[[Mackey topology]]''' on ''X'' or the '''[[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X, X*)|topology of uniform convergence on the convex balanced weakly compact subsets of ''X\u2032'']]''' and <math>X_{\\tau\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or <math>X_{\\tau}</math> denotes ''X'' endowed with this topology. <math>\\tau(X, X^{\\prime})</math> is the finest locally convex TVS topology on ''X'' whose continuous dual space is equal to <math>X^{\\prime}</math>. \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X*, X)|\ud835\udf0f(X\u2032, X)]] denotes the '''[[Mackey topology]]''' on ''X\u2032'' or the '''[[Topology of uniform convergence#Mackey topology \u03c4(X*, X)|topology of uniform convergence on the convex balanced weakly compact subsets of ''X'']]''' and <math>X_{\\tau\\left(X^{\\prime}, X\\right)}</math> or  <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}</math> denotes ''X'' endowed with this topology. \n** Note that <math>\\tau\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right) \\subseteq b\\left( X^{\\prime}, X) \\subseteq \\tau \\left( X^{\\prime}, X^{\\prime\\prime} \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=432-434}} \n* [[Topology of uniform convergence#Convergence on equicontinuous sets \u03b5(X, X*)|\u03b5(X, X\u2032)]] denotes the '''topology of uniform convergence on equicontinuous subsets of X\u2032''' and <math>X_{\\epsilon\\left(X, X^{\\prime}\\right)}</math> or  <math>X_{\\epsilon}</math> denotes [[Topology of uniform convergence#Convergence on equicontinuous sets \u03b5(X, X\u2032)|''X'' endowed with this topology]]. \n** If ''H'' is a set of linear mappings <math>X \\to Y</math> then ''H'' is [[equicontinuous]] if and only if it is equicontinuous at the origin; that is, if and only if for every neighborhood ''V'' of ''0'' in ''Y'', there exists a neighborhood ''U'' of ''0'' in ''X'' such that <math>\\lambda (U) \\subseteq V</math> for every <math>\\lambda \\in H</math>.\n\n== Definition ==\nThroughout let ''X'' and ''Y'' be [[topological vector space]]s with continuous dual spaces <math>X^*</math> and <math>Y^*</math>. Note that almost all results described are independent of whether these vector spaces are over <math>\\mathbb{R}</math> or <math>\\mathbb{C}</math> but to simplify the exposition we will assume that they are over the field <math>\\mathbb{C}</math>. \n\n=== Continuous bilinear maps as a tensor product ===\nNote that the question of whether or not one vector space is a [[tensor product]] of two other vector spaces is a purely algebraic one (i.e. the answer does not depend on the topologies of ''X'' or ''Y''). Nevertheless, the vector space <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> of continuous bilinear functionals is always a tensor product of ''X'' and ''Y'', as we now describe. \n\nFor every <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> we now define bilinear form, denoted by the symbol ''x \u2297 y'', from <math>X^{\\prime} \\times Y^{\\prime}</math> into the underlying field (i.e. <math>x \\otimes y : X^{\\prime} \\times Y^{\\prime} \\to \\mathbb{C}</math>) by \n: <math>\\left(x \\otimes y\\right) \\left(x^{\\prime}, y^{\\prime} \\right) := x^{\\prime}(x) y^{\\prime}(y)</math>. \nThis induces a canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to \\mathcal{B}\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> defined by sending <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> to the bilinear form <math>x \\otimes y</math>. \nThe span of the range of this map is <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math>. \nThe following theorem may be used to verify that <math>B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> together with the above map \u2297 is a tensor product of ''X'' and ''Y''. \n\n'''Theorem''' Let ''X'', ''Y'', and ''Z'' be vector spaces and let <math>T : X \\times Y \\to Z</math> be a bilinear map. Then the following are equivalent:{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=403-404}} \n# ''(Z, T)'' is a [[tensor product]] of ''X'' and ''Y'';\n# (a) the image of ''T'' spans all of ''Z'', and (b) ''X'' and ''Y'' are ''T''-linearly disjoint (this means that for all positive integers ''n'' and all elements <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_n \\in X</math> and <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n \\in Y</math> such that <math>\\sum_{i=1}^{n} T(x_i, y_i) = 0</math>, (i) if all <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_n</math> are linearly independent then all <math>y_i</math> are 0, and (ii) if all <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n</math> are linearly independent then all <math>x_i</math> are 0).\n:* Equivalently, ''X'' and ''Y'' are ''T''-linearly disjoint if and only if for all linearly independent sequences <math>x_1, \\ldots, x_m</math> in ''X'' and all linearly independent sequences <math>y_1, \\ldots, y_n</math> in ''Y'', the vectors <math>\\left\\{ T(x_i, y_j) : 1 \\leq i \\leq m, 1 \\leq j \\leq n \\right\\}</math> are linearly independent.\n\n=== Topology ===\n\nHenceforth, all topological vector spaces considered will be assumed to be locally convex. \nIf ''Z'' is any locally convex topological vector space, then for any [[equicontinuous]] subsets <math>G \\subseteq X^{\\prime}</math> and <math>H \\subseteq Y^{\\prime}</math>, and any neighborhood <math>N</math> in ''Z'', define \n:<math>\\mathcal{U}(G, H, N) = \\{b \\in \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right) : b(G, H) \\subseteq N\\}</math>\nIt can be shown that every set <math>b(G, H)</math> is bounded, which is necessary and sufficient for the collection of all such <math>\\mathcal{U}(G, H, N)</math> to form a locally convex TVS topology on <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> called the '''\u03b5-topology'''. When <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> (resp. <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, etc.) is endowed with the \u03b5-topology, it will be denoted by <math>\\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math> (resp. <math>\\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, <math>B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right)</math>, etc.). \n(Note that <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right) \\subseteq B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Z \\right) \\subseteq \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{b}, Y^{\\prime}_{b}; Z \\right)</math>). \n\nIn particular, when ''Z'' is the underlying scalar field then since <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math>, we will denote <math>B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> by <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math>, which is called the '''injective tensor product''' of ''X'' and ''Y''. The space <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is not necessarily complete so we denote its completion by <math>X \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} Y</math>. The space <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is complete if and only if both ''X'' and ''Y'' are complete, in which case the completion of <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math> is a subvector space of <math>\\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right)</math>.\n\n=== Canonical identification of separately continuous bilinear maps with linear maps ===\nOne may show that the set equality <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right) = L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math> holds (i.e. if <math>u : X^{\\prime} \\to Y</math> is a linear map, then <math>u : X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y_{\\sigma\\left( Y, Y^{\\prime} \\right)}</math> is continuous if and only if <math>u : X^{\\prime}_{\\tau\\left(X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y</math> is continuous, where here ''Y'' has it's original topology).{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}}   \n\nThere is also a canonical vector space isomorphism <math>J : \\mathcal{B}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( Y^{\\prime}, Y \\right)} \\right) \\to L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma \\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)}; Y_{\\sigma \\left( Y, Y^{\\prime} \\right)} \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}}  \nTo define it, for every separately continuous bilinear form <math>B</math> defined on <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\times Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( Y^{\\prime}, Y \\right)}</math> and every <math>x^{\\prime} \\in X^{\\prime}</math>, let <math>B_{x^{\\prime}} \\in \\left( Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)^{\\prime}</math> be defined by <math>B_{x^{\\prime}}\\left( y^{\\prime} \\right) := B\\left( x^{\\prime}, y^{\\prime} \\right)</math>. \nSince <math>\\left( Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)^{\\prime}</math> is canonically vector space-isomorphic to ''Y'' (via the canonical map <math>y \\mapsto </math> value at ''y''), we will identify <math>B_{x^{\\prime}}</math> as an element of ''Y'', which we'll denote by <math>\\tilde{B}_{x^{\\prime}} \\in Y</math>. \nThis defines a map <math>\\tilde{B} : X^{\\prime} \\to Y</math> given by <math>x^{\\prime} \\mapsto \\tilde{B}_{x^{\\prime}}</math> and so the canonical isomorphism is of course defined by <math>J(B) := \\tilde{B}</math>. \n\nWhen <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> is given the topology of uniform convergence on equicontinous subsets of ''X\u2032'', the canonical map becomes a TVS-isomorphism <math>J : \\mathcal{B}_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right) \\to L_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=428-430}} In particular, <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y = B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> can be canonically TVS-embedded into <math>L_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\tau}; Y \\right)</math>; furthermore the image in <math>L\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}; Y_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> of <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y = B_{\\epsilon}\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma} \\right)</math> under the canonical map ''J'' consists exactly of the space of continuous linear maps <math>X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma\\left( X^{\\prime}, X \\right)} \\to Y</math> whose image is finite dimensional.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | pp=432-433}}\n\n== Relation to projective tensor product and nuclear spaces ==\nThe [[strongest]] locally convex topology on <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math> making the canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to B\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> (defined by sending <math>(x, y) \\in X \\times Y</math> to the bilinear form <math>x \\otimes y</math>) continuous is called the '''projective topology''' or the '''\u03c0-topology'''. When <math>B\\left( X^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}, Y^{\\prime}_{\\sigma}\\right) = X \\otimes Y</math> is endowed with this topology then it will be denoted by <math>X \\otimes_{\\pi} Y</math> and called the '''projective tensor product''' of ''X'' and ''Y''. \n\n\n== Canonical identifications of bilinear and linear maps ==\nIn this section we describe canonical identifications between spaces of bilinear and linear maps. These identifications will be used to define important subspaces and topologies (particularly those that relate to [[nuclear operator]]s and [[nuclear space]]s).\n\n== Properties ==\n\n* The canonical map <math>\\cdot \\otimes \\cdot : X \\times Y \\to \\mathcal{B}\\left( X_{\\sigma}^{\\prime}, Y_{\\sigma}^{\\prime} \\right)</math> is continuous.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=434}} \n* If ''X'' and ''Y'' are normed then <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math> is normable. \n* <math>X \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y</math> is Hausdorff if and only if both ''X'' and ''Y'' are Hausdorff.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=434}}\n* Suppose that <math>u : X_1 \\to Y_1</math> and <math>v : X_2 \\to Y_2</math> are two linear maps between locally convex spaces. If both ''u'' and ''v'' are continuous then so is their tensor product <math>u \\otimes v : X_1 \\otimes_{\\epsilon} X_2 \\to Y_1 \\otimes_{\\epsilon} Y_2</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=439}}\n** If ''u'' and ''v'' are both TVS-isomorphisms then so is <math>u \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} v : X_1 \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} X_2 \\to Y_1 \\widehat{\\otimes}_{\\epsilon} Y_2</math>.{{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=440}}  \n* The \u03b5-topology is always finer than the [[Projective tensor product|\u03c0-topology]] and coarser than the [[inductive topology]] (which is the finest locally convex TVS topology making <math>X \\times Y \\to X \\otimes Y</math> separately continuous).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Final topology]]\n* [[Projective tensor product]]\n* [[Nuclear operator]]s\n* [[Nuclear space]]s\n* [[Topological tensor product]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book | last=Diestel | first=Joe | title=The metric theory of tensor products : Grothendieck's r\u00e9sum\u00e9 revisited | publisher=American Mathematical Society | publication-place=Providence, R.I | year=2008 | isbn=0-8218-4440-7 | oclc=185095773 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Diestel | 2008 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Dubinsky | first=Ed | title=The structure of nuclear Fr\u00e9chet spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1979 | isbn=3-540-09504-7 | oclc=5126156 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Dubinsky | 1979 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Grothendieck | first=Grothendieck | title=Produits tensoriels topologiques et espaces nucl\u00e9aires | publisher=American Mathematical Society | publication-place=Providence | year=1966 | isbn=0-8218-1216-5 | oclc=1315788 | language=fr | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Grothendieck | 1966 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Husain | first=Taqdir | title=Barrelledness in topological and ordered vector spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1978 | isbn=3-540-09096-7 | oclc=4493665 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Husain | 1978 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Khaleelulla | first=S. M. | title=Counterexamples in topological vector spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1982 | isbn=978-3-540-11565-6 | oclc=8588370 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Khaleelulla | 1982 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Nlend | first=H | title=Bornologies and functional analysis : introductory course on the theory of duality topology-bornology and its use in functional analysis | publisher=North-Holland Pub. Co. Sole distributors for the U.S.A. and Canada, Elsevier-North Holland | publication-place=Amsterdam New York New York | year=1977 | isbn=0-7204-0712-5 | oclc=2798822 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Nlend | 1977 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Nlend | first=H | title=Nuclear and conuclear spaces : introductory courses on nuclear and conuclear spaces in the light of the duality | publisher=North-Holland Pub. Co. Sole distributors for the U.S.A. and Canada, Elsevier North-Holland | publication-place=Amsterdam New York New York, N.Y | year=1981 | isbn=0-444-86207-2 | oclc=7553061 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Nlend | 1981 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Pietsch | first=Albrecht | title=Nuclear locally convex spaces | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin,New York | year=1972 | isbn=0-387-05644-0 | oclc=539541 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Pietsch | 1972 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Robertson | first=A. P. | title=Topological vector spaces | publisher=University Press | publication-place=Cambridge England | year=1973 | isbn=0-521-29882-2 | oclc=589250 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Robertson | 1973 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Ryan | first=Raymond | title=Introduction to tensor products of Banach spaces | publisher=Springer | publication-place=London New York | year=2002 | isbn=1-85233-437-1 | oclc=48092184 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Ryan | 2002 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Schaefer | first=Helmut H.| title=Topological Vector Spaces | publisher=Springer New York Imprint Springer | series=[[Graduate Texts in Mathematics|GTM]] | volume=3 | publication-place=New York, NY | year=1999 | isbn=978-1-4612-7155-0 | oclc=840278135 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Schaefer | 1999 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | last=Treves | first=Francois | title=Topological vector spaces, distributions and kernels | publisher=Dover Publications | publication-place=Mineola, N.Y | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-486-45352-1 | oclc=853623322 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Treves | 2006 | p=}} -->\n* {{cite book | author=Wong | title=Schwartz spaces, nuclear spaces, and tensor products | publisher=Springer-Verlag | publication-place=Berlin New York | year=1979 | isbn=3-540-09513-6 | oclc=5126158 | ref=harv}} <!-- {{sfn | Wong | 1979 | p=}} -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/nuclear+space Nuclear space at ncatlab]\n\n{{Template:Functional analysis}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n", "name_user": "Mgkrupa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Injective_tensor_product"}
{"title_page": "Tinglof Peninsula", "text_new": "[[File:Thurston Island - en.svg|thumb|Map of Thurston Island.]]\n[[File:ThurstonIsland Terra MODIS.jpg|thumb|Satellite image of Thurston Island.]]\n'''Tinglof Peninsula''' ({{coord|72|2|S|100|6|W|||display=inline,title}}) is an ice-covered [[peninsula]], 10 nautical miles (18&nbsp;km) long, between [[Henry Inlet|Henry]] and [[Wagoner Inlet]]s on the north side of [[Thurston Island]]. Delineated from aerial photographs taken by [[U.S. Navy Operation Highjump]] in December 1946. Named by [[Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names]] (US-ACAN) for [[Iver (Ivor) Tinglof]]<ref>[https://hdl.handle.net/1811/64529ab8-b684-46da-9194-ef082fc28419 \"Cover to Byrd's Wife from Crew Member\"], The Ohio State University Libraries. Retrieved 2020-03-31.</ref>, tractor mechanic of the [[Richard_E._Byrd#Second_Antarctic_expedition|Second Byrd Antarctic Expedition]] in 1933\u201335, who built at [[Little America (exploration base)|Little America]] the first heavy cargo sleds for use in the Antarctic.<ref>{{cite gnis|type=antarid|id=15326|name=Tinglof Peninsula|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nSmith Cliff is a rock cliff midway along the ice-covered northern shore of the peninsula. It was photographed by the Eastern Group of Operation Highjump and later named by US-ACAN after Aviation Radioman William F. Smith an aircrewman from the operation.<ref>{{cite gnis|type=antarid|id=18588|name=Smith Cliff|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n* [http://www.pgc.umn.edu/maps/antarctic/id/ANT_REF-MA2508-009 Thurston Island \u2013 Jones Mountains.] 1:500000 Antarctica Sketch Map. US Geological Survey, 1967.\n* [http://www.add.scar.org Antarctic Digital Database (ADD).] Scale 1:250000 topographic map of Antarctica. Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research (SCAR). Since 1993, regularly upgraded and updated.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{USGS}}\n\n[[Category:Peninsulas of Ellsworth Land]]\n\n\n{{ThurstonIsland-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Thurston Island - en.svg|thumb|Map of Thurston Island.]]\n[[File:ThurstonIsland Terra MODIS.jpg|thumb|Satellite image of Thurston Island.]]\n'''Tinglof Peninsula''' ({{coord|72|2|S|100|6|W|||display=inline,title}}) is an ice-covered [[peninsula]], 10 nautical miles (18&nbsp;km) long, between [[Henry Inlet|Henry]] and [[Wagoner Inlet]]s on the north side of [[Thurston Island]]. Delineated from aerial photographs taken by [[U.S. Navy Operation Highjump]] in December 1946. Named by [[Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names]] (US-ACAN) for [[Iver (Ivor) Tinglof]]<ref>[https://hdl.handle.net/1811/64529ab8-b684-46da-9194-ef082fc28419 \"Cover to Byrd's Wife from Crew Member\"], The Ohio State University Libaries. Retrieved 2020-03-31.</ref>, tractor mechanic of the [[Richard_E._Byrd#Second_Antarctic_expedition|Second Byrd Antarctic Expedition]] in 1933\u201335, who built at [[Little America (exploration base)|Little America]] the first heavy cargo sleds for use in the Antarctic.<ref>{{cite gnis|type=antarid|id=15326|name=Tinglof Peninsula|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\nSmith Cliff is a rock cliff midway along the ice-covered northern shore of the peninsula. It was photographed by the Eastern Group of Operation Highjump and later named by US-ACAN after Aviation Radioman William F. Smith an aircrewman from the operation.<ref>{{cite gnis|type=antarid|id=18588|name=Smith Cliff|accessdate=2018-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n* [http://www.pgc.umn.edu/maps/antarctic/id/ANT_REF-MA2508-009 Thurston Island \u2013 Jones Mountains.] 1:500000 Antarctica Sketch Map. US Geological Survey, 1967.\n* [http://www.add.scar.org Antarctic Digital Database (ADD).] Scale 1:250000 topographic map of Antarctica. Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research (SCAR). Since 1993, regularly upgraded and updated.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{USGS}}\n\n[[Category:Peninsulas of Ellsworth Land]]\n\n\n{{ThurstonIsland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tinglof_Peninsula"}
